# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The **160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne)**, abbreviated as **160th SOAR(A)**, is a special operations force of the United States Army that provides helicopter aviation support for special operations forces.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Its missions have included attack, assault, and reconnaissance, and these missions are usually conducted at night, at high speeds, low altitudes, and on short notice.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Nicknamed the **Night Stalkers** and called **Task Force Brown** within the JSOC, the 160th SOAR(A) is headquartered at Fort Campbell, Kentucky.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The 160th SOAR(A) consists of some of the Army's best-qualified aviators, crew chiefs, and support soldiers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Officers are all volunteers; enlisted soldiers volunteer or are assigned by the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Until 2013, only men were allowed to be pilots in the 160th.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Upon joining the 160th, all soldiers are assigned to "Green Platoon", in which they receive intensive training in "advanced methods of the five basic combat skills: first responder, land navigation, combatives, weapons and teamwork".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The weapons training includes firing thousands of rounds with M4/M4A1 carbines and SIG Sauer M17/M18 pistols.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Soldiers who fail the course the first time may retake it, but there is no guarantee that anyone assigned to Green Platoon will pass and continue on with the 160th.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The basic Night Stalker course for enlisted soldiers lasts five weeks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The officer course lasts 20 to 28 weeks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] A new Night Stalker pilot arrives at a unit as Basic Mission Qualified (BMQ).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] After a series of skills test qualifications, experience, leadership, and oral review boards lasting up to three years, the Night Stalker is designated Fully Mission Qualified (FMQ).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] After three to five years as an FMQ, the Night Stalker may be nominated and assessed by a long process consisting of several flight evaluations to earn the flight lead qualification.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] SOAR flight medics can qualify as special operations combat medics by completing the 36-week Special Operations Combat Medic (SOCM) course at Fort Bragg.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] After the April 1980 Operation Eagle Claw attempt to rescue American hostages held in Tehran, Iran, failed, President Jimmy Carter ordered former Chief of Naval Operations Adm.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Holloway III to determine how the U.S. military could best mount another attempt.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] At the time there were no U.S. helicopter units trained in this kind of stealthy, short-notice Special Operations mission.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The chosen pilots immediately entered intensive training in night flying.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] This provisional unit was dubbed Task Force 158, since most of its pilots were Black Hawk aviators detached from the 158th.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Their distinctive 101st "Screaming Eagle" patches remained on their uniforms.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The Black Hawks and Chinooks continued to operate around Campbell Army Airfield at the north of the post, and Saber Army Heliport at the south.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] OH-6 Cayuses, aircraft that had vanished from the division after Vietnam, were hidden on base in an ammunition holding area still known as the "SHOC Pad", for "Special Helicopter Operations Company".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] As the first batch of pilots completed training in the fall of 1980, a second attempt to rescue the hostages was planned for early 1981.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Dubbed Operation Honey Badger, it was called off when the hostages were released on the morning of President Ronald Reagan's inauguration.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Task Force 158 was the Army's only special operations aviation unit, and its members had already become recognized as the Army's premier aviation night fighters.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Their capability was judged too useful to lose, and so instead of returning to the 101st, the pilots and modified aircraft became a new unit.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Original members of the Night Stalkers refer to it as "the day the Eagles came off".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] They were originally created as Task Force 160, when the 101st Airborne Division was commanded by Jack V.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] When the command was formally organized as a regiment, Mackmull was chosen to serve as its honorary colonel.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The unit was officially established on 16 October 1981, when it was designated the 160th Aviation Battalion.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In 1983, the 160th first saw combat during Operation Urgent Fury, the U.S. invasion of Grenada.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In 1986, it was renamed the 160th Aviation Group (Airborne).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In May 1990, their name changed to the 160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] As demand for highly trained special operations aviation assets bloomed, the regiment activated three battalions, a separate detachment, and incorporated one Army National Guard unit, the 1st Battalion, 245th Aviation (OK ARNG).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In 1987 and 1988, its pilots took part in Operation Earnest Will, the protection of re-flagged Kuwaiti tankers in the Persian Gulf during the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] They flew from US Navy warships and leased oil barges in a secret sub-part called Operation Prime Chance.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] They became the first helicopter pilots to use night vision goggles and forward looking infrared (FLIR) devices in night combat.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In June 1988, the unit received a short-notice directive to recover a Soviet made Mi-25 Hind (Mi-24 Hind export version) attack helicopter from a remote location in Chad.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The Hind was abandoned by the Libyans after 15 years of fighting, and was of great intelligence value to the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In April 1988, two CH-47 Chinooks, a U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Air Force C-5 Galaxy, and 75 maintenance personnel and crew flew to White Sands AFB, New Mexico, to rehearse the mission.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In late May 1988, an advance team went to Ndjamena, Chad, to await their aircraft.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Two weeks later, two Chinooks and 76 crew members and maintenance personnel arrived by C-5.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] At midnight on 11 June 1988, two MH-47s flew 490 miles at night without outside navigational aids to the target location, the Ouadi Doum Airfield in northern Chad.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The first Chinook landed and configured the Hind, while the second hovered overhead and sling loaded it for return to Ndjamena.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] A surprise sandstorm slowed the return trip, but less than 67 hours after the arrival of the C-5 in Chad, the ground crew had the Hind and Chinooks aboard and ready for return to the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In 1989, the Night Stalkers spearheaded Operation Just Cause, the invasion of Panama.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In 1991, they participated in Iraq, during Operation Desert Storm.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In October 1993 in Somalia, Night Stalkers fought in the Battle of Mogadishu, which became the subject of the book *Black Hawk Down* and its film adaptation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Two Night Stalker Black Hawks were shot down in the battle: Super 6–1, piloted by Cliff Wolcott, and Super 6–4, piloted by Mike Durant.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Five of the eighteen men killed (not counting a nineteenth post-operation casualty) during the battle were members of the Night Stalkers team, who were lost along with the two aircraft.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] During the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan, the Night Stalkers from 2nd Battalion supported two task forces established in early October 2001: Dagger and Sword.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Their unit in TF Sword was designated Task Force Brown.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The pilots of the Chinooks, flying in zero-visibility conditions, were refueled in flight three times during the 11-hour mission, establishing a new world record for combat rotorcraft.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The troops—two 12-man Green Beret teams from the 5th Special Forces Group dubbed Operational Detachment Alpha (ODA) 555 and 595 plus four Air Force Combat Controllers—linked up with the CIA and Northern Alliance.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Within a few weeks, the Northern Alliance, assisted by U.S. ground and air forces, captured several key cities from the Taliban.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In November 2001, Night Stalker AH-6J Little Birds took part in Objective Wolverine and Raptor missions and Operation Relentless Strike.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In December 2001, Night Stalker crews resupplied more than 150 Delta Force, British Special Boat Service, and CIA Special Activities Division operatives as they hunted for Osama bin Laden in the Tora Bora mountain complex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In March 2002, Night Stalkers from B Company, 2nd Battalion, 160th SOAR supported coalition troops during Operation Anaconda.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] At the Battle of Takur Ghar on 4 March, one of their MH-47Es, callsign Razor 03, was damaged by rocket-propelled grenades and crash-landed carrying Mako 30.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] A second MH-47E, callsign Razor 01, responded with a Quick Reaction Force; it was damaged by small arms and rocket-propelled grenades, and crash-landed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] One Night Stalker was killed in the battle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In June 2002 in the Philippines, Night Stalker MH-47Es were involved in the operation that killed Abu Sabaya, a senior leader in Abu Sayyaf.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Predator drone marked Sabaya with an infrared laser as he tried to escape in a smuggler's boat.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The MH-47Es trained searchlights on the boat while operators from the Philippine Naval Special Operations Group opened fire, killing the terrorist leader and capturing four other terrorists with him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Later in 2002, in Afghanistan, Task Force 11 (previously known as Task Force Sword but renamed in January 2002) was composed of DEVGRU and a company of Rangers, and was supported by a company of helicopters from the 160th SOAR.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] During the 2003 invasion of Iraq, 3rd Battalion, 160th SOAR, deployed as the Joint Special Operations Air Detachment-West under CJSOTF-West (Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force-West/Task Force Dagger).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] It was equipped with eight MH-47E Chinooks, four MH-60L DAPs, and two MH-60L Black Hawks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] At 9 p.m. on 19 March 2003, the first strike of Operation Iraqi Freedom was carried out by members of the 160th SOAR, on Iraqi visual observation posts along the southern and western borders of Iraq.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The strike groups included one flight of MH-60L DAPs and four "Black Swarm" flights, each consisting of a pair of AH-6M Little Birds; a FLIR-equipped, target-spotting MH-6M; and a pair of U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In seven hours, more than 70 sites were destroyed, effectively depriving the Iraqi military of any early warning of the coming invasion.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] As the sites were eliminated, the first heliborne SOF teams launched from H-5 airbase in Jordan, including vehicle-mounted patrols from the British and Australian special forces, who were transported by the MH-47Es of the 160th SOAR.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Night Stalkers from 1st Battalion 160th SOAR, they were based at Ar'Ar, supported Task Force 20 with MH-60L/K Black Hawks, MH-60L DAPs, MH-6M transport, and AH-6M Little Birds.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 26 March, the 160th SOAR took part in the Objective Beaver mission, a raid by DEVGRU on al Qadisiyah Research Centre, which was suspected to have stocks of chemical and biological weapons.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 1 April 2003, the 160th SOAR took part in the rescue of PFC Jessica Lynch, who had been taken prisoner during the Battle of Nasiriyah.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 2 April, a Delta Force squadron operating in Iraq was ambushed by a half-dozen armed technicals from an anti-special forces Fedayeen.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Two MH-60K Black Hawks carrying a parajumper medical team and two MH-60L DAPs of the 160th SOAR responded and engaged the Iraqis, which allowed the Delta operators to move their two casualties to an emergency HLZ.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] One Delta Force operator succumbed to his wounds.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On the evening of 13 December 2003, Saddam Hussein was captured by U.S. forces in Operation Red Dawn.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] He was exfiltrated by a MH-6 Little Bird from the 160th SOAR and he was taken into custody at Baghdad International Airport.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In 2004, they took part in the rescue of three Italian contractors and one Polish businessman held for ransom by Iraqi insurgents.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In Afghanistan in 2005, eight Night Stalkers (four from HHC and four from Bravo company of 3rd Battalion) were killed along with eight Navy SEALs on a rescue mission for Marcus Luttrell, after their MH-47 Chinook helicopter was hit by a rocket propelled grenade.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] They were sent out to look for Luttrell after Operation Red Wings, in which he was involved with three other SEALs, was compromised and Luttrell's teammates killed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In March 2006, SEALs from DEVGRU and Rangers were flown by the 160th SOAR into in North Waziristan, Pakistan, to assault an al-Qaeda training camp, allegedly under the codename: Operation Vigilant Harvest, the assaulters killed as many as 30 terrorists including the camp's commandant.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 14 May 2006, helicopters from the 160th SOAR brought operators from Delta Force's B Squadron to Yusufiyah, Iraq, to fight al-Qaeda fighters in several buildings.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] As the operators disembarked their helicopters, they came under fire from a nearby house, and more al-Qaeda fighters soon joined the firefight.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The door gunners of the 160th's Black Hawks fired at the insurgents; a pair of AH-6M Little Birds carried out strafing runs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] One Little Bird from the 160th's 1st Battalion, B Company, was shot down.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] An estimated 25 al-Qaeda fighters were killed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In July 2006, a pair of MH-47Es from 160th SOAR attempted to insert a combined strike element of DEVGRU, Rangers, and Afghan commandos in Helmand Province, Afghanistan, to attack a compound.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] With some troops on the ground, a large insurgent force ambushed them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Both helicopters were struck by small arms fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] One MH-47E pilot put his aircraft in the line of fire to protect the other MH-47E as its assault team disembarked.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] An RPG hit the shielding MH-47E, whose pilot crash-landed with no serious injuries to operators or aircrew.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The Ranger commander and an attached 2nd Commando Regiment operator organised an all-round defence while the other MH-47E held back the advancing insurgents until its miniguns ran out of ammunition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] An AC-130 Spectre joined the battle and kept the down crew and passengers safe until a British Immediate Response Team helicopter recovered them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The AC-130 then destroyed the MH-47E wreck, denying it to the Taliban.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Elements of 3rd Battalion 160th SOAR have conducted episodic deployments in support of Operation Enduring Freedom—Caribbean and Central America, begun in 2008.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Night Stalker helicopters were present during the 2008 SOCOM counter-terror exercises in Denver.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 24 April 2008, Company D, 3rd Battalion, 160th SOAR was inactivated at a ceremony conducted at Hunter Army Airfield, Georgia, as part of a regimental transformation plan.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The 160th SOAR also took part in the 2008 Abu Kamal raid.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 19 August 2009, four Night Stalkers from D Company, 1st Battalion, 160th SOAR lost their lives in a MH-60 Black Hawk helicopter crash in Leadville, Colorado, during mountain and environmental training.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 9 September 2009 in Afghanistan, Night Stalkers inserted the British SBS and SFSG into Kunduz Province to rescue *Times* journalist Stephen Farrell after he and his Afghan interpreter were captured by the Taliban.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In September 2009 in Somalia, the Night Stalkers took part in Operation Celestial Balance, whose target was a senior terrorist leader connected to al-Qaeda affiliated organizations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The assault force (4 AH-6M Little Birds and 4 MH-60L Black Hawks) carried in DEVGRU operators to kill or capture the leader.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] AH-6Ms strafed the two-vehicle convoy, killing the leader along with three other al-Shabaab terrorists, then carried out an overwatch while DEVGRU cleared the vehicles and recovered the body.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 22 October 2009, a 3rd Battalion helicopter crashed into the USNS *Arctic* during a joint training exercise involving fast roping about 20 miles off Fort Story, Virginia.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The crash killed a soldier, Sergeant First Class James R.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Stright, 29, and injured eight others, three seriously.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In May 2011, the Night Stalkers took part in the raid on Osama bin Laden's compound.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The operation involved flying covertly into Abbottabad, Pakistan in a pair of MH-60 Black Hawk helicopters, specially modified for stealth and piloted by the 160th SOAR, to take a team of Navy SEALs directly to bin Laden's compound.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] While one of the helicopters crash landed on arrival, all on board survived.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The SEALs were successfully inserted onto the property while the crew was able to extract themselves, provide cover for the SEALs and then leave on the other helicopter.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The mission was overall considered a success.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The dramatic nighttime raid was "painstakingly recreated" in the film *Zero Dark Thirty*, which covers the CIA's efforts to track down bin Laden, from just after the September 11th attacks to the daring raid ten years later.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 28 May 2012, Operation Jubilee took place: Black Hawks from the 160th SOAR flew in teams from the British 22 SAS and DEVGRU into Badakhshan Province, Afghanistan to rescue a British aid worker, a Kenyan NGO worker and 2 Afghans who were taken hostage by bandits in the province.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 15 January 2014, a MH-60M Black Hawk of the 160th performed a hard landing at Hunter Army Airfield in Georgia.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] One soldier, CPT Clayton Carpenter of NY, posthumously promoted to MAJ, was killed, with another two injured.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 4 July 2014, during Operation Inherent Resolve, the Night Stalkers inserted Delta Force operators into Syria to rescue James Foley and other US hostages.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] One American was wounded, no hostages were found, but a substantial number of terrorists were killed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] CENTCOM mistakenly posted a video on the internet of a flight of four MH-60Ms of the 160th SOAR conducting a mid-air refueling over Iraq in October 2014, the video was hastily taken down.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 26 November 2014, MH-60s flown by Nightstalkers took part in the first raid in the 2014 hostage rescue operations in Yemen.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The Night Stalkers continue to be deployed to Afghanistan as part of NATO's Resolute Support Mission after Operation Enduring Freedom-Afghanistan ended in late 2014 and was replaced with Operation Freedom's Sentinel.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Throughout the night of 5 December 2015, a group of Rangers engaged in a firefight with enemy troops near the Afghan-Pakistan border.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] After about 5 a.m. their commander called for an extraction after they learned of a larger enemy group approaching.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] An arriving helicopter from the 160th SOAR and came under heavy enemy fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] An AH-64 Apache from the 1st Battalion, 101st Aviation Regiment, which was escorting the helicopter, positioned itself directly between the U.S. troops, the extraction helicopter, and the enemy forces to draw fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] As a result, the extraction was successful.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 29 January 2017, the 160th SOAR took part in the Yakla raid in Yemen, distinguishing itself when its helicopters flew repeatedly into heavy enemy fire to support U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 25 August 2017, a Black Hawk helicopter flown by the 160th SOAR crashed off the coast of Yemen while conducting hoist training, when it lost power and crashed into the sea.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] Six servicemen survived, one US service member remained missing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 27 October 2017, a US helicopter from 4th Battalion 160th SOAR crashed in Logar province, Afghanistan, killing one and injuring six more US service members.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] The crash was not a result of enemy action.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On 20 August 2018, CW3 Taylor Galvin died from injuries resulting from an MH-60M crash while conducting a partnered counter-terrorism mission in support of the Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On September 18, 2021, a man wielding a katana attacked several SOAR soldiers at Inyokern Airport in California, wounding two and forcing more than twenty of them, including at least one staff sergeant and one captain, to "hunker down" in a hangar.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On November 10, 2023, five SOAR troops died when a UH-60 Black Hawk crashed in the Mediterranean Sea 30 miles off the coast of Cyprus during a training exercise.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] On September 17, 2025, an MH-60 crashed near Summit Lake, in Washington, forty miles from Joint Base Lewis–McChord, killing the four soldiers on board.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In October 2025 SOAR elements were deployed to the Caribbean in the wake of the Trump administration's declaration of a "non-international armed conflict" with "unlawful combatants" alleged to be involved in trafficking drugs to the US.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In January 2026, during the 2026 United States strikes in Venezuela, SOAR elements flew over Caracas to capture Venezuelan president Nicolás Maduro and his wife Cilia Flores prior to him being indicted for Narcotics and Terrorism charges.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] In April 2026, SOAR elements participated in 2026 United States F-15E rescue operation in Iran during the 2026 Iran war.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/160th-special-operations-aviation-regiment-airborne] A MH-47G conducts Maritime External Air Transportation System (MEATS) training with the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The **1811 German Coast uprising** was a slave rebellion which occurred in the Territory of Orleans on January 8–10, 1811.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] It occurred on the east bank of the Mississippi River in the modern-day Louisiana parishes of St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebellion was the largest of its kind in the history of the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels killed two white slave owner family members, but the confrontations with the U.S. military and local militiamen who were sent to suppress the rebellion, combined with post-trial executions, resulted in the deaths of 95 rebels.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 8, between 64 and 125 slaves ignited a fight for freedom and marched from plantations in and near present-day LaPlace, Louisiana on the German Coast towards New Orleans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] More people escaped slavery and joined them along the way, and some accounts claimed a total of 200 to 500 people escaped and participated in the rebellion.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] During their two-day, 20 mi (32 km)-long march the rebels, armed mostly with improvised weapons, burned five plantations along with several sugarhouses and crop fields.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] After a few planters were killed and others attacked, White settlers led by U.S. officials formed militia companies.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In battle on January 10 they killed 40 to 45 of the people escaping slavery, while suffering no fatalities themselves, then hunted down and killed several other people without trial.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Over the next two weeks, White planters and U.S. officials interrogated, tried, executed, and decapitated an additional 44 people escaping slavery who had been captured.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Executions were generally by hanging or firing squad.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Heads were displayed on pikes to intimidate others.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration in January of the uprising, in which they have been joined by some descendants of participants in the revolt.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sugar boom on what was known as Louisiana's German Coast (named for immigrants in the 1720s) began after the American Revolutionary War, while the area near New Orleans was still controlled by Spain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the 1780s Jean Saint Malo, an escaped slave, established a colony of maroons in the swamps below New Orleans, which eventually led Spanish officials to send militia to capture him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Saint Malo became a folk hero after his execution in New Orleans on June 19, 1784.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] A decade later, during the height of the French Revolution, Spanish officials discovered a slave conspiracy at Pointe Coupee (established by French settlers around 1720 between Natchez and New Orleans).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] That slave uprising during the Easter holidays was suppressed before it came to fruition and resulted in 23 executions by hanging (with the severed heads then displayed on the road to New Orleans), and 31 additional slaves were flogged and sent to serve hard labor in other Spanish outposts.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the Haitian Revolution, planters established similar lucrative sugarcane plantations in the Gulf Coast area, resulting in a dense slave population.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] They converted from cotton and indigo plantations to sugarcane, so that by 1802, 70 sugar plantations produced over 3,000 tons annually.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some accounts claimed blacks outnumbered whites by nearly five to one by 1810, and about 90% of whites in the area enslaved people.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] More than half of those enslaved may have been born outside Louisiana, many in Africa, where various European nations established slave trading outposts and Kongo was ripped apart by civil wars.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the U.S. negotiated the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, both the Marquis de Lafayette and James Monroe declined to become the governor of the Territory of Orleans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] President Thomas Jefferson then turned to a fellow Virginian, William C.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne, whom he appointed on an interim basis and who arrived in New Orleans with 350 volunteers and 18 boats.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne struggled with the area's diverse population, particularly because he spoke neither French nor Spanish.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The population also included a larger proportion of native Africans among the slaves than elsewhere in the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In addition, the mixed-race Creole and French-speaking population grew markedly with refugees from Haiti (and their slaves) following the successful Haitian Revolution.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne was not used to a society with the number of free people of color that Louisiana had, but he worked to continue their role in the militia that had been established under Spanish rule.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Long-term French Creole residents complained to Washington, D.C., about Claiborne and new U.S. settlers in the territory, and wanted no part of President Jefferson's plan to pay 30,000 Americans to move into the new territory and amalgamate with the residents.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, by 1805, a delegation led by Jean Noël Destréhan went to Washington to complain about the "oppressive and degrading" form of the territorial government, but President Madison continued to support Claiborne, who had expressed great doubts about the planters' honesty and trustworthiness.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Lastly, Claiborne suspected that the Spanish in nearby West Florida might encourage an insurrection.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, he struggled to establish and maintain his authority.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the overall Territory of Orleans, from 1803 to 1811, the free black population nearly tripled, to 5,000, with 3,000 arriving as migrants from Haiti (via Cuba) in 1809–1810.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In Saint-Domingue they had enjoyed certain rights as *gens de couleur*, including owning slaves themselves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Furthermore, between 1790 and 1810, slave traders brought around 20,000 enslaved Africans to New Orleans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The masters and slaves were virtually all Catholic.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The waterways and bayous around New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain made transportation and trade possible but also provided easy escapes and nearly impenetrable hiding places for runaway slaves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some maroon colonies continued for years within several miles of New Orleans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] With the spread of ideas of freedom from the French and Haitian Revolutions, European Americans worried about slave uprisings, particularly in the Louisiana area.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 1805, they heard a traveling Frenchman was preaching about liberty, equality, and fraternity to the French-speaking slaves, and arrested him as dangerous.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] A group of slaves met on January 6, 1811.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] It was a period when work had relaxed on the plantations after the fierce weeks of the sugar harvest and processing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] As planter James Brown testified weeks later, "The black Quamana [Kwamena, meaning "born on Saturday"], owned by Mr.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Brown, and the mulatto Harry, owned by Messrs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Kenner and Henderson, were at the home of Manuel Andry on the night of Saturday–Sunday of the current month in order to deliberate with the mulatto Charles Deslondes, chief of the brigands." Slaves had spread word of the planned uprising among the slaves at plantations up and down the German Coast.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The revolt began on January 8 at the Andry plantation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] After striking and badly wounding Andry, the slaves killed his son Gilbert.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] "An attempt was made to assassinate me by the stroke of an axe", Andry wrote.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] "My poor son has been ferociously murdered by a horde of brigands who from my plantation to that of Mr.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The approximately 15 slaves at Andry's plantation, about 30 miles (50 km) upriver from New Orleans, joined another eight slaves from the next-door plantation of the widows of Jacques and Georges Deslondes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] This was the home plantation of Charles Deslondes, a slave driver (a slave overseer of other slaves) later described by one of the captured slaves as the "principal chief of the brigands".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Small groups of slaves joined from every plantation the rebels passed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Witnesses remarked on their organized march.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] They carried mostly pikes, hoes, and axes, but few firearms, and they marched to drums while some carried flags.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Approximately 10–25% of any given plantation's slave population joined with them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the plantation of James Brown, Kook, one of the most active participants and key figures in the story of the uprising, joined the insurrection.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the next plantation down, Kook attacked and killed François Trépagnier with an axe.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] He was the second and last planter killed in the rebellion.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the band of slaves passed the LaBranche plantation, they stopped at the home of the local physician.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Finding him gone, Kook set his house on fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some planters testified at the trials in parish courts that they were warned by slaves of the uprising.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Others regularly stayed in New Orleans, where many had town houses, and trusted their plantations to overseers to run.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Planters quickly crossed the Mississippi River to escape the insurrection and to raise a militia.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] As those escaping moved downriver, they passed larger plantations, from which other slaves joined them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Numerous slaves joined the insurrection from the Meuillion plantation, the largest and wealthiest plantation on the German Coast.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels laid waste to Meuillion's house.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] They tried to set it on fire, but a slave named Bazile fought the fire and saved the house.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising started in present-day LaPlace and followed a 20-mile trek on the old River Road through the present-day towns of Montz, Norco, New Sarpy, Destrehan, St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Rose and ended at much of what had once been the Kenner and Henderson Plantations and is now Rivertown and Louis Armstrong International Airport in Kenner.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] After nightfall the escaping slaves reached Cannes-Brulées, about 15 miles (24 km) northwest of New Orleans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The men had traveled between 14 and 22 miles (23 and 35 km), a march that probably took them seven to ten hours.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] By some accounts, they numbered "some 200 slaves", although other accounts estimated up to 500.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] As typical of revolts of most classes, free or slave, the insurgent slaves were mostly young men between the ages of 20 and 30.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] They represented primarily lower-skilled occupations on the sugar plantations, where slaves labored in difficult conditions with a low life expectancy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Despite his injuries, Andry crossed the river and made contact with other planters, raising a militia and pursuing the escaping slaves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] By noon on January 9, the residents of New Orleans had heard about the insurrection.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] By sunset, General Wade Hampton I, Commodore John Shaw, and Claiborne sent two volunteer militia companies, 30 US Army soldiers, and 40 US Navy sailors to fight the escaping slaves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] By about 4 a.m. on January 10, this force had reached Jacques Fortier's plantation, where Hampton thought the escaped slaves had encamped overnight.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] However, the escaped slaves had started back upriver about two hours earlier, had traveled about 15 miles (24 km) back up the coast, and had neared Bernard Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] There, planter Charles Perret, in cooperation with Andry and Judge St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, had assembled a militia of about 80 men from the river's opposite side.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] At about 9 o'clock, this militia force discovered escaping slaves moving toward high ground on Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret ordered his men to attack the escaping slaves, which he later wrote numbered about 200 men, about half on horseback.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] (Most accounts said only the leaders were mounted, and historians believe it unlikely the escaping men could have gathered so many mounts.) Within a half-hour, 40 to 45 escaping people had been killed; the remainder slipped away into the woods and swamps.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret's and Andry's militias tried to pursue them despite the difficult terrain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 11, the militia, assisted by Native American trackers as well as hunting dogs, captured Deslondes, whom Andry considered "the principal leader of the bandits." A slave driver and son of a white man and a slave, Deslondes received no trial or interrogation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The following day Pierre Griffee and Hans Wimprenn, who were thought the murderers of M.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] François Trépagnier, were captured, killed, and their heads decapitated for delivery to the Andry estate.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Major Milton and the dragoons from Baton Rouge arrived and provided support for the militia, since Hampton believed them supported by Spanish authorities in West Florida.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Having suppressed the insurrection, the planters and government officials continued to search for people who had escaped.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Those captured later were interrogated and jailed before trials.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Officials convened three tribunals: one at Destrehan Plantation in St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, and the third in New Orleans (Orleans Parish).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Destrehan trials, overseen by Judge Pierre Bauchet St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, resulted in the execution of 18 of 21 captured people by firing squad.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some slaves testified against others, but others refused to testify or submit to the all-planter tribunal.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In New Orleans, Commodore Shaw presumed that "but few of those who have been taken were acquitted." The New Orleans trials resulted in the conviction and summary executions of 11 more slaves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Three were publicly hanged in the *Place d'Armes*, now Jackson Square.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] One of those spared was a 13-year-old boy, who was ordered to witness another man's death and then received 30 lashes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Another escaped person was treated with leniency because his uncle turned him in and begged for mercy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sentence of a third person was commuted because of the valuable information he had given.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heads of those executed were put on pikes and the mutilated bodies of dead rebels displayed to intimidate other slaves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The naval officer Samuel Hambleton described the heads posted on stakes that lined the levee as follows, "They were brung up here for the sake of their Heads, which decorate our Levee, all the way up the coast.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] U.S. territorial law provided no appeal from a parish court's ruling, even in cases involving imposition of a death sentence on a slave.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In fact, Claiborne did commute two death sentences, those of Henry and Theodore, each referred by the Orleans Parish court.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] No record has been found of any referral from the court in St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Charles Parish, or of any refusal by the governor of an application for clemency.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Militias killed about 95 slaves between the battle, subsequent summary apprehensions and executions, as well as by execution after trials.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] From the trial records, most of the leaders appeared to have been mixed-race Creoles or mulattoes, although numerous slaves were native-born Africans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Fifty-six of the slaves captured on January 10 and involved in the revolt were returned to their masters, who may have punished them but wanted their valuable laborers back to work.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thirty more escaping slaves were captured and returned to their masters after planters determined they had been forced to join the revolt by Deslondes and his men.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heirs of Meuillon petitioned the legislature for permission to free the mulatto slave Bazile, who had worked to preserve his master's plantation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Not all the slaves supported insurrection, knowing the trouble it could bring and not wanting to see their homes and communities destroyed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising was short-lived and quickly crushed by local authorities.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Showing planter influence, the legislature of the Territory of Orleans approved compensation of $300 to planters for each escaping slave killed or executed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The territory gratefully accepted the presence of U.S. troops after the revolt.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The national press covered the insurrection, with some Northerners seeing it arising out of the wrongs suffered under slavery.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration at Norco in January, where they have been joined by some descendants of members of the revolt.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] While the Destrehan Plantation tour concentrates on architecture and white lifestyle and family histories, a small museum in a converted slave cabin (not on the standard tour) features folk paintings of the 1811 uprising.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] More recently, the Whitney Plantation, in St.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, opened in 2014 and is the first plantation museum in the country dedicated to the slave experience.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Whitney Plantation includes a memorial and information to commemorate the 1811 Slave Uprising of the German Coast.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2015, artist Dread Scott began organizing a massive re-enactment of the uprising; the 26 mile, 2-day event took place in November 2019.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising is featured in Talene Monahon's 2020 play about historical reenactment, *How to Load a Musket*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2021, the 1811 Kid Ory Historic House opened on the site of Woodland Plantation in LaPlace, which is in the National Register of Historic Places of the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1811-german-coast-uprising] The museum is dedicated to the German Coast uprising and to Kid Ory, an American jazz composer, trombonist, and bandleader born there in 1886.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The **Fiji Expedition of 1840** was an exploring and surveying expedition, which itself was a part of the wider United States Exploring Expedition (a.k.a. the **Wilkes expedition** or the **U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.**) that occurred from May 4 to August 11, 1840.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It produced several scientific and cultural breakthroughs in realms such as cartography, oceanography, volcanology, anthropology, ethnography, ethnology, philology, linguistics, geology, taxonomy, trade, diplomacy, toponymy, epidemiology, pathology and Christian missionary work.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It also was known for two separate punitive expeditions against separate groups of Fijians.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. under the command of Lieutenant Charles Wilkes had just discovered that Antarctica was a continent, and finished surveying Wilkes Land.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes was facing a significant deadline.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was originally given a deadline of 3 years to conduct the necessary research for all the allotted study location goals for the expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Unfortunately for him he only had two months to conduct the studies for Fiji expedition, then he would immediately have to journey to the Columbia river expeditions to finish the rest of the studies for the rest of the year.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If Wilkes did not, the sailors' and marines' enlistment service would expire, and the expedition's future would have been put in jeopardy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This situation put Wilkes under immense pressure.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As it was, besides the Columbia river expedition, the Fiji expedition was considered the most paramount research destination for several reasons.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] New England merchants and whalers frequented Fiji for its whale and sandalwood, and competed with the British and the French for the bêche-de-mer populations to sell in China.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Fiji possessed many uncharted reefs, rocks, and currents, with a culture well known for its cannibalism (in fact for a while Fiji was also known as the Cannibal Isles) and a noted penchant for dragging boats to shore and killing all on board.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] No dependable navigation charts existed, and in the 12 years prior to 1840, 8 ships (5 of them being American) had been destroyed in the area.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] These conditions made travel to and around these Islands so precarious, the East India Marine Society of Salem, Massachusetts, United States had petitioned the federal government for local charts for sailors navigating these waters.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Although surveying was the primary reason for the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. also brought along a group of scientists which were also deployed for the Fiji expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now that the Antarctic discoveries were finished, Wilkes' fleet traveled to Sydney, Australia, then to the Bay of Islands, New Zealand, and finally they rendezvoused at Tongatapu, in Tonga, and prepared for their next mission in Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes had already had his four ships refitted at Sydney.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His current fleet at the time of the Fiji expedition consisted of Wilkes' flagship the USS *Vincennes* (sloop-of-war, 780 tons, 18 guns), the USS *Peacock* (sloop-of-war, 650 tons, 22 guns), the USS *Porpoise* (brig, 230 tons, 10 guns), and the USS *Flying Fish* (schooner, 96 tons, 2 guns).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Furthermore, Wilkes had at least a dozen gigs, cutters, and whaleboats prepared for travel against the hazardous reefs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes' fleet set sail out of Nukuʻalofa on May 4, 1840.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He dispatched the *Porpoise* under Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold to the Lau Group of the Fiji Islands, while the rest of the fleet went to the Koro Sea.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The 3 ships headed for the Island of Ovalau, but by the morning of May 7, the *Flying Fish* under the command of Lieutenant George Sinclair went missing, after it got caught on a reef.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes pressed on with the *Peacock* and the *Vincennes* and anchored by the village Levuka.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon Wilkes arrival, a white shipwrecked survivor of the Oneo a Nantucket man named David Whippey and one of his sons paddled up to the *Vincennes.* Whippey was what was called a beachcomber, which in this context meant a "tame white man" to the Fijians.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was a sort of mercenary, military advisor, and translator.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The earliest beachcomber Charlie Savage and those like him taught Fijians how to use fire arms.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This revolutionized Fijian warfare, and they were greatly valued by war chiefs, who rewarded them with riches and women.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey had risen to the title of "Mata-ki-Bau" (the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes arranged for Whippey to have him meet the chief or "Tu'i" of Levuku.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes bestowed several gifts upon the chief, who in gratitude and with Whippey's aid sent a message to Tanoa high King *Vunivalu* of Bau (called "Old Snuff by the local whites) and head of the notorious Lasakau sea warriors, and asked to meet with him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a messenger was sent, Whippey took Wilkes and 25 of his officers and naturalists (including the commander of the *Peacock* Lieutenant William L.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson and Navy Geographer and passed midshipman Henry Eld), along with an entourage of natives, on a tour and hike of Mount Nadelaiovalau.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At the top of the mountain Wilkes and his scientists could clearly see the surrounding area including nearby reefs and other nearby landmarks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The group set out right away making charts, sketches, measurements for recording, and collecting plant and animal specimens.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 8 Wilkes deployed two surveying parties on boats.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One was to be led by Lieutenant James Alden Jr. who would leave Ovalau to explore the northern shore of Viti Levu Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The second boat was led by Lieutenant George F.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons, who in turn scouted the south shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave the officer further orders that after exploring their respective shores that they should assemble at the Island of Malolo which was to the west of Viti Levu.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day Lieutenant Sinclair arrived with the *Flying Fish* at Levuka and reported to Wilkes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 11 Wilkes decided to build an observatory of tents, houses, and a small research garden.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was situated 30 feet above the beach on a peak near Levuku village, and above Vi Tonga village as a forward operating center for the Fiji Expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The observatory was erected on May 11, with guards surrounding the perimeter.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 12, Chief Tanoa arrived in a finely decorated 100 foot, double hulled, outrigger canoe with a sail and a 40-man crew.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He boarded the Vincennes and through Whippey was able to negotiate a trade deal between Bau and the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A few days later, Wilkes received Seru Epenisa Cakobau the son and crown prince of Tanoa, who further cemented bonds of the Bau nation and the expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Seru would one day come to unite the Kingdoms of Bau, Rewa, and Naitasiri into the short lived Kingdom of Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Tanoa was the King of Bau, he exercised the greatest influence among all the other kingdoms of the islands of Fiji, Tui Levuku was in charge of Ovalau Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With the aid of Whippey, Tui Levuku helped the Americans maintain their supply lines, trade with Levuku village, and receive information through the first six weeks of the Fiji expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a few says an Irish beachcomber named Paddy O'Connell entered Wilkes, tent on Ovalu.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell attempted to hire himself out to Wilkes, but Wilkes dismissed him at first.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, a single story caught his interest.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell informed Wiles that he was a witness to the murder of several of the crew of the American bêche-de-mer merchant ship the *Charles Doggett* in August 1834, on Ono Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes learned that a Fijian chief named Veidovi was the man who organized the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] According to O'Connell he was a crewman of the *Charles Doggett* when the incident occurred.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In this instance Captain Bachelor of the *Charles Doggett* made a contract with a chief named Veidovi for *bêche-de-mer* on Rewa.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the *Charles Doggett* reached Rewa, it was agreed that a minor chief would willingly be taken hostage for the protection of the Westerners while they set up a *bêche-de-mer* house on shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the chief feigned sickness and was allowed to return to shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the minor chief returned with Veidovi and some of his men and asked for medicine at the *bêche-de-mer* house.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mate, eight other men, and a boy came ashore, all except one were killed, robbed, and the house was house set on fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the captain, through O'Connell, was able to negotiate for all the bodies back except an African American crewmate whose body was eaten.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later O'Connell became a beachcomber and discovered that while Veidovi was the primary perpetrator of this attack, the other chiefs of Rewa and especially Veidovi's kin endorsed the killings.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon hearing this story Wilkes became angry and sent O'Connell to Lieutenant Hudson on the *Peacock* to arrest Veidovi.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell met Hudson and gave him Wilkes' orders.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair of them set out for Rewa in Viti Levu where Veidovi lived.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was there that Hudson eventually met with King Kania or Roko Tui Dreketi/King of Rewa and Methodist missionaries of the English Wesleyan Mission who helped him get the lay of the land.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After assessing the political landscape, Hudson quickly concocted a plan to trap Veidovi.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 21 Hudson invited the King Kania and his three brothers on board the *Peacock* to a welcoming reception.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Between 70 and over 100 local Fijians showed up along with the Tui Dreketi himself, but Veidovi was noticeably absent.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson lured the native royals into his cabin with an offering of a meal and then called for battle stations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The royals were split away from their retainers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson promised mercy to the chiefs in exchange for them delivering Veidovi to them, and causing no harm to the local missionaries.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a spout of protest the King Kania agreed, and two of the chiefs brothers were released to arrest Veidovi dead or alive.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The following day Veidovi arrived and agreed to go quietly in exchange for the freedom of his family and their families respectively.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson took Veidovi to his personal cabin for interrogation and Veidovi openly conceded to orchestrating the *Charles Doggett* killings.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi explained that he lured the mate of the ship into a trip and feigned a friendly greeting to the mate of the ship.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then his men seized the mate and clubbed him to death, and then proceeded to kill more of the ship hands.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi added that his motivations were to acquire firearms and that he was only following his culture in that "...he had only followed the Fegee customs and done what his people had often done before.".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson decided to punish Veidovi by forcing him to travel with the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and then live in America for a few years, where he would learn to be civilized and not kill white people.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi was dismayed, since as a chief he had 55 wives and numerous children that he would have to leave behind.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson then headed for Kadavu Island where it was said more of the perpetrators of the attack on the *Charles Doggett* resided.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, the wind was against him, and suffering for a lack of time in his other duties for the expedition, Hudson satisfied himself with the capture of Veidovi and returned to Levuka.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Word traveled fast of Veidovi's capture, it spread to the village of Levuka, and then to Wilkes himself.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey and Tui Levuku soon caught wind of a plot to capture Wilkes in order to entice and exchange of prisoners (Wilkes for Veidovi).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The suspected perpatrtors would have been King Tanoa who was allies with King Kania.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the Mountains of Ovalau resided the Livoni tribe who were allied with Tanoa.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes remained armed, furnished himself an escort, he ordered 40 men to reinforce the observatory.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes then took Seru hostage on board the *Vincennes*, repositioned the guns of the *Vincennes* to a more defensible position.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes also brought his dog Sydney with him (which terrified the natives), and an attempted kidnapping never materialized.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In early June, a British expedition consisting of the HMS Sulphur (1826) HMS Starling (1829)) commanded by Captain Edward Belcher arrived in Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was conducting his own separate surveying expedition and had just come from the Vavaʻu island group in Tonga.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher traveled to Rewa where the Sulphur had lost a rudder from hitting a reef.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After Belcher's expedition encountered other members of the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and through messengers, Wilkes gave Belcher a spare rudder from the fleet.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, Wilkes came to meet Belcher aboard his ship, and they spoke together in Belcher's cabin.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, despite Wilkes' goodwill in offering Belcher an extra rudder, Belcher was less than pleased to see him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was required to pay port charges due to the trade deal that he had set up between the U.S. and chief Tanoa.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The meeting did not accomplish much, although Wilkes found out that Belcher had explored the Columbia River the year before in 1839, and based on Belcher's descriptions Wilkes believed he would definitely need to extend the length of the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The two parted cordially and Belcher and his ships later sailed to Vanuatu.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Chief Tui Levuku decided to honor the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. with a traditional Club dance/Meke called the Meke I Wau or Meke Mada on June 24 at Levuku village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Over a hundred Fijians and their chiefs from Levuku and other nearby villages attended.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans were directed to the Mbure/temple, or spirit-house, which had an elevated platform where they could more easily observe the festivities.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The location overlooked the village from where they observed a low square stone wall on the opposite end of the street.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On one end many Fijians sat down awaiting the performance and on the opposite were several Fijian musicians.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually a "Feejee Clown" emerged in the center of the crowd, and began to galivant and dance wildly, to the delight and laughter of all.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown's body was completely enveloped with green and brown leaves and several vines, except for his face to which he wore a mask.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes stated that to him the mask looked somewhat like the face of a bear.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mask was painted black on one half and orange on the other.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown danced with one large club in one hand and a shorter one on the other.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the clown performed, the musicians began to play with hand claps, sticks, and bamboo joints which made a soft drumming sound.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Roughly 100 club dancers were waiting behind a rock until they were ready.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they emerged in a column of two and began to proceed down the street at a slow three step pace.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They all wore the white *I-sala* turban typically worn by priests and chiefs as well as a white Masi tapa cloth to cover themselves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Their sala were decorated with flowers and vines, and their faces were painted in various patterns of black and vermillion.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the dance columns advanced they split up from two columns to three and then to four and danced and swung their clubs in a variety of motions and poses.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They danced into the square and joined the clown and the musicians.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The dancers began singing with the musicians and their dances became more rapid and volatile, before they concluded their song and dance with a loud cry of "Wha---hoo".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the presentation had concluded the dancers laid their clubs down in a pile before the Americans as a gift to them, but they expected to receive gifts in return.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day Wilkes gave gifts on behalf of the expedition to Chief Tui Levuku so that he might distribute them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after the end of the club dance festival, Wilkes decided to pack up the observatory and move on to other areas of the Fijian Islands.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Before the expeditions departure the purser Robert Waldron purchased and donated land for the construction of a Methodist mission school, with both a school house and chapel led by John Hunt.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following this, the *Vincennes* departed on the 28th of June, to survey the hot springs of Savusavu on the Island of Vanua Levu.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Peacock* had several accidents associated with or on it during this expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At Vita Levu the ship sustained considerable, but non fatal damages to its hull.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While one of the Peacocks cutter boats had overturned and sank.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point one man lost three fingers to an anchor chain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On another occasion a man accidentally shot off his index finger.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A third sailor nearly had his leg entirely detached.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, another sailor had an accident while winding the capstan and broke his ribs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, perhaps the worst accident occurred on June 29 when 2nd mate Joseph Baxter of the *bêche-de-mer* *Leonidas* unwittingly placed a gunpowder cartridge under his shirt while preparing to fire a cannon (for non offensive purposes).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A spark flew off from the igniter and hit the cartridge the man was carrying which exploded over three pounds of gunpowder, and the man was badly charred from the ordeal.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Baxter was later transferred to the Peacock for medical attention.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He confessed that he was a French man whose real name was Vincent Boudet.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] During one occasion of the expedition the *Peacock* was off the coast of Tavea when a chief and his wife and an escort of three canoes approached the ship.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hoping to antagonize the crew, the natives explained that they had captured three prisoners from an enemy village and had "roasted them and eaten part!".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They displayed a piece of one of the bodies that had been preserved in plantain leaves to show the crew.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they produced a half gnawed on skull to be exhibited.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crew also noticed one native eating an eyeball, with flesh dangling from his mouth.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Some of the men vomited at this spectacle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the Waldron bought the skull to be added to the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s artifact collection in exchange for some cloth.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] William Brackenridge the horticulturalist and Charles Pickering the naturalist teamed up to make several discoveries together while at Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With their mutual cooperation, they discovered over 650 different plant species.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included a new species of tomato and poison ivy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Pickering made the discovery that if the science team did not bring anything that appeared valuable to the natives, they could travel about the Islands without great fear of danger or harassment.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This gave them ample time an opportunity to conduct their research.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And Brackenridge, for his part, found the last existing variant of sandalwood on Fiji, which up until that point was thought to have been extinct from over harvesting.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Horatio Hale, the teams' philologist and anthropologist, documented over 5,600 words in the Fiji language and documented their craftsmanship in producing various canoes, dwellings, and pottery.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] James Dwight Dana the team's geologist made a titanic discovery in his field.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He proved Charles Darwin's theory of subsidence, which Darwin had spoken about publicly, but was formally addressed in his book *The Structure and Distribution of Coral Reefs*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the theory of subsidence after a volcanic Island is formed and after a lengthy period of time a fringing reef forms along the edges or "fringes" of the Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After that and given more time the Island begins to erode and sink and a lagoon begins to form around the island and the fringing reef becomes a barrier reef.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then after further erosion and sinking over time the island sinks into the sea and only the reef and lagoon it forms remains becoming an atoll.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Darwin at first thought he could not adequately prove his theory, but Dana proved it by finding all 3 stages of reef formations on the islands of Cicia, Matuku, and Nanuku.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s surgeons was able to study a number of local diseases endemic to Fiji on Ovalau, as well as the natives methods for treating them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these diseases included a disease the Fijians of the time called "dthoke" which has similarities to both lupus and yaws, and may be mistaken for secondary stage syphilis.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another was a Fijian form of influenza called the "dandy cough" that the natives believe spread and mutated through contact with contact from white people, or as the Fijian's called them "Papalangi".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox believed this influenza may have come from an influenza epidemic that had spread in the USA a few years before the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox recorded reports from many local whites that about a tenth of the Fijian population had died during that time.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 11th, the *Vincenees*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* were surveying in Bua Bay, Bua, Vanua Levu.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes dispatched, Lieutenant Oliver Hazard Perry Jr.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] (of the Perry Family) and passed midshipman Samuel R.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox 20 miles southeast, to lead a two cutter survey to chart Solevu bay.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair and their crews had been stuck in the bay by a storm for numerous days, with dwindling supplies.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the boats were anchored a group of natives taunted them threateningly from the beach.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually their food ran out and both Perry and Knox felt compelled to escape.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The winds blew hard as the crew made for the shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon disembarking the boat, the sailors were encircled by several natives with clubs, spears, and a small amount of firearms.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews gunpowder was wet and so if it came down to a fight the crew would need to resort to hand-to-hand combat.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in an unprecedented move by Western accounts the chief in charge of the natives took pity on the explorers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox and his men swam back to Perry's boat, which became overloaded.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As night fell, the natives lit fires on the beach and occasionally took pot shots at Perry and his men.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the cover of night, the natives stealthily began diving and swimming to the boat, and attempted to either lift the anchor or cut the anchor chain to drag the boat ashore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The sailors began firing into the water, and eventually were able to capture two of the tribesmen who swam to the boat and made an effort to appear to be allies.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry suspected them as spies and so arrested them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out they were both chiefs one of high rank and one of low rank.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon taking these men hostage, the natives on the shore made no more attempts to go after the boat that night.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was supposed that they feared the death of their chiefs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When morning came Perry made a second attempt to escape the bay.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This time he attempted to maneuver his cutter around the shallow reefs and into the open ocean.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Natives, realizing what Perry was attempting to accomplish, assembled around the edges of the reef.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point the boat struck a reef and took on water.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men attempted to bail and keep their distance from the natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry was able to escape with his crew and prisoners.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 12, Perry met with the *Vincennes*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* which had all rendezvoused at Bua Bay.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After learning what had happened, Wilkes assembled 11 boats, 80 men, and the *Flying Fis*h to exact retribution, and retrieve the stolen cutter.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The flotilla arrived in the afternoon at low tide.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the waters were shallow a mudflat had formed between Wilkes' ships and the stolen cutter.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes met with the chiefs representatives and used Whippey as a translator.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes commanded the natives to return the boat and all items that were in it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were intimidated as up until this point in Fijian history there was never before a time when so many westerners had gathered threatening war.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The chief returned the boat, but did not return the boats equipment and belongings of the crew.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Outraged Wilkes landed most of his men armed with muskets, but remained on a gig from which he would direct a Congreve rocket.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes ordered the burning of Solevu village and the politically linked nearby village of Tye.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Combined the fighters of these villages were between 150 and 200 warriors.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, both the warriors and the populace fled into the hills and Wilkes fired rockets into the village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The villages were destroyed, but due to the simplicity of the villages' material, the structures would be repaired in a few weeks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Aside from loss or damage to property no side suffered any casualties.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following the burning of the villages, and in an act of good will, Wilkes released the two captured chiefs and bestowed them with valuable gifts.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His logic was that they came bearing friendship and aid to Perry's crew.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was also done to demonstrate to the natives that hostility to Americans (and white people in general) would be met with vengeance, and cordiality met with reward.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. soon moved on from Solevu to the Mamanuca Islands to continue their survey mission, while the Vincennes and Peacock deployed to Muthuata Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey informed Wilkes that this set of islands was particularly notorious for being perilous to westerners, as the residents of Malolo were noted for being pirates and the worst offenders of attacking foreigners.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes acknowledged the danger and made sure his boats were grouped together and well escorted.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He deployed three boats and the *Porpoise* and *Flying Fish* for this mission.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The boats were led by Lieutenants Alden, Emmons, and Joseph Underwood.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 22 the squadron reached Drawaqa Island at the southern most end of the Yasawa Islands.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent two boats led by Alden and Underwood to the middle of the Mamanucas, the *Porpoise* took the Western side, and the *Flying Fish* and Emmons' cutter took the Western end.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The goal was for all three groups to complete their surveying that day and then assemble together at Malolo Island the next day.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 24, Alden and Underwood finished their surveying without issue, and anchored on the east side of Malolo next to Malolo Lailai for the night.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning Underwood and Alden noticed the *Flying Fish* and Emmons boat anchored in the distant East along Malolo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An hour later, Emmons boat approached Underwood and Alden's.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They inquired for food, but Emmons regrettably told them that the *Flying Fish* was entirely bereft of anymore supplies.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This distressed the officers as only a few days ago Wilkes had cut the food rations by a third due to low provision levels, and currently Underwood and Alden's men only had a few yams with them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was decided to try and trade with the local natives for food.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood encountered a Fijian boy chief in the area, who was carrying war clubs which struck him as menacing, and so arrested him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, he found a group of local natives and through a Māori interpreter named John Sac, Underwood negotiated for food.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood was able to negotiate a tentative deal between himself and the natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The village of Malolo was on the Southwest part of the island and the natives proposed making an exchange for a few hogs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in order to get them Underwood would have to accompany the natives and one of the boats would have to sail to the Southwestern part of the island to pick them up.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out that the local chief's son was the man that Underwood had captured.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In light of this, Underwood agreed to travel with the natives to their village provided that the chiefs son stay with his boat as a captive and guarantee of Underwood's safety, and would be released when business was concluded.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood used his own boat (the *Leopard*) as it was smaller than Alden and Emmons cutters and could more easily go over the shallows without getting trapped.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He left all but three of his muskets with the *Porpoise* in order to further reduce weight and increase the ease of travel.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was actually against the standing orders that Wilkes had laid out for safety, but Underwood did not believe that the Fijians were as dangerous as was commonly supposed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood brought Sac with him to translate, along with six other men.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the men stayed with the *Leopard* (commanded by Alden) and their hostage on the beach.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood met a group of natives near the village by a tree.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tree had many throwing and maiming clubs tied to the branches, and two thin hogs next to it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood tried to barter for the swine, but he was informed that no transaction could be made without the chiefs approval.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After half an hour the chief appeared after returning from a fishing trip.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Chief demanded a musket with ammo and powder in exchange for the hogs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Meanwhile, Alden and his men had waited in their boat a short distance from the shore, however their men were becoming agitated.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tide was coming in and Alden didn't trust the natives as much as Underwood did.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A messenger soon came from Underwood giving him an update of the situation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden sent a message to Underwood to stop negotiating and return to the ship.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent Wilkes' Nephew Midshipman Wilkes Henry (who was named after his Uncle), to deliver the message.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after, a Canoe came up alongside the *Leopard* and began talking to the chief's son.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Fijian attempted to get out of the boat, but Aden pulled him down.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another half an hour passed, and negotiations seemed to be progressing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another messenger from Underwood informed Alden that the chief wanted a hatchet and then the hogs would go to the sailors.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden gave the man the hatchet and he ran to give it to Underwood.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Not long after Emmons arrived in one of the cutters.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He and his crew had been looking for an area to eat the pigs at the nearby Malolo Lailai island, and began discussing it with Alden.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was sharing with Emmons his anxieties over the negotiations and the chief's son's attempted escape, when the native leaped out of the boat and made for the opposite direction from the village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered one of his men to shoot over the chief's head to entice him to return.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Accounts differ as to what happened next, however when the shot went off.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden and Emmons claimed that the chief's son's escape attempt was a signal for the natives to attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While those who were negotiating with the chief claimed that the attack began after the shot was fired.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Either way, the chief shouted that he thought that the sailors on the beach had killed his son, and ordered an assault.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Two Fijians grabbed the musket of one of Underwood's men, named Joseph Clark.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark gripped the musket and then brandished a knife.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He stabbed one native and then bashed another with the muskets' shoulder stock.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, several natives began spilling out of the mangrove bushes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's men began to fire their muskets as they retreated to the two boats.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] About 100 natives began to give chase to the men retreating on the beach and threw spears and throwing clubs at their enemy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes Henry and Underwood covered the retreat.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry was hit by a club and then shot the man who threw it at him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then another native hit him in the back of the head.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry collapsed to the ground with his face in the water, was surrounded by natives, and then stripped.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Joseph Clark was hit by a glancing blow in the mouth and the spear landed in Underwood's left arm.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark shot the man who threw the spear in the head and then another native knocked Clark out with a club.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He fell into the water, but the pain from the salt water on his bloody face soon woke him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark stood up and witnessed Underwood being clubbed in the back of the head.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark attempted to drag Underwood to safety with one arm, and hit away other natives with his other.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Clark was hit twice more and fell down.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got back up when he noticed another native was about to club the unconscious Underwood and stabbed him repeatedly.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark grabbed Underwood again who briefly came to and told him to tell his wife he loved her.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Underwood had his head clubbed in and died.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark was left in a state of shock and delirium.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got up and limped to the rest of the escaping sailors.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark's face was covered in blood and dangling flesh and in his absent minded state, he laughed and sang at the natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were perplexed by Clark's actions and stayed clear of him for the rest of the engagement.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Besides Clark, all the men who retreated back to the beach that survived suffered injuries.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Aldan and Emmons saw the fighting on the beach their crews began to row for the shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the other retreating men had assembled at the boats with Alden and Emmons, Alden a handful of men went back to look for Underwood and Henry.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They encountered Clark in his delusional state and sent him back to the boats.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had retreated back to their village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Alden and his men found the bodies of both of Underwood and Henry almost completely naked.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's face was smashed beyond recognition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As for Henry, aside from the bruising and his nudity, Henry looked unharmed, but his mourners soon realized that Henry had drowned while unconscious.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the beach, there lay the bodies of ten Fijians from the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of them stirred and was still alive, and in a fit of fury and vengeance the men, shot and stabbed him several times, before cutting off his head.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of the men, wanted to pursue the natives back to their village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] But there were less than two dozen men, and the natives could return at any moment and overwhelm them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden commanded the men make a swift retreat back to the rest of the expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The bodies of Henry and Underwood were gingerly placed in the cutter and covered in jackets to uphold their dignity, and the two boats sailed back to the *Flying Fish*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the bodies were brought on board they were placed in the ships port side and covered with a tarp.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The cadavers were stitched into hammocks, draped in flags, buried on a nearby small island, and hidden out of fear that the natives would dig up and cannibalize the bodies.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes named the Island Henry Island after his Nephew (not to be confused with Henry Island (Washington), which he also named after his Nephew later in the expedition).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That night (July 24) Wilkes set up boat patrols commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Eld around Malolo to ensure no native escaped.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It became evident that the natives also expected a counterattack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fijians in full war paint and equipped with muskets were scattered around the shoreline and would fire pot shots at the boat crews.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews would occasionally fire back, but the natives would take cover and drop prone before a musket ball could hit them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes sent a force of about 70 men and a Fijian scout in 3 divisions.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The force was commanded by Lieutenant Ringgold, they landed in Southern Malolo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave orders to kill all men and burn the village, but "spare only the women and the children.".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From there the men began marching to the fortified village of Sualib just outside of where Underwood and Henry were killed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* waited on the coast with their cannons fixed on the shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* was originally going to lead the boats into battle, but it grounded on a sandbar.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the meantime Wilkes organized a small fleet of boats commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Clark whose mission was to search and destroy all hostile escaping canoes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] There other objective was to approach the smaller Arro (sometimes called Yaro) village and neutralize it while Ringgold's force would destroy Sualib and link up with Wilkes flotilla in Arro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the landing party was disembarking, three canoes appeared and were headed to Malolo Lailai.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and Alden took two boats and pursued them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once they were close enough an interpreter asked the natives where they were from.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native responded that they were from Malolo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed six natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the natives jumped in the water.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered that the rest be taken as prisoners, but his men had bloodlust and shouted "Kill" repeatedly.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One man grabbed a Fijian woman by the hair and was about to slash her with his sword when Alden aimed his pistol at him.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was able to reign in his men and together with Emmons, and they captured several men, women, and children, including a chief from Arro village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men were handcuffed and kept captive, but the women and children were released on the beach.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Emmons and Alden were occupied capturing the natives during their engagement, Wilkes proceeded with his boats to Arro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He found the village deserted, and put it to the flame.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men had gone ahead to join the defense of Sualib and the women and children had fled to the mountains.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes continued on and hoped to reinforce Ringgold at Sualib, but found it destroyed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He doubled back and later met Ringgold at Arro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ground force landed at 10 A.M. and divided up in to three groups as Wilkes had ordered.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The groups were led by Lieutenants Ringgold, Robert Johnson and Andrew Murray, and included passed midshipman Henry Eld and Alfred Thomas Agate of the science corps.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ringgold gave a short speech and reminded the men to destroy everything except the women and children.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The forces split up into different paths and destroyed farms along the way, before meeting up and surrounded the fort.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort itself was circular, with a 12 foot wide by 6 feet deep ditch/dry moat which they used as a trench, and a ten foot tall coconut tree and whicker palisade on all sides.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had occupied the trench and the palisade edges, and together they either aimed their muskets outside of the trench through small holes in the palisade walls.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of chiefs, recognizable by their white headdresses, commanded the warriors in between the trenches and stockade.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The warriors began to shout obscenities at the oncoming attackers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans fired a Congreve rocket and their muskets at the fort, and the Fijians quickly dashed into the fort.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The enemy retreated, a portion of Johnson's division, without orders stormed the fort.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The attack was spearheaded by Sinclair with a double barrel shotgun.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Sinclair entered the fort he quickly realized that it was a trap.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ditch which had been built outside of the palisades also extended into the interior and was occupied by a large number of natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included women armed with bows who fought with their men.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Retreat for Sinclair and his advance was impractical and decidedly more dangerous than it was worth.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort was purposefully built like a fish weir trap, with a wide opening, but a narrow avenue of escape.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair got shot with an arrow in his lapel, but it only penetrated the fabric of his coat and not the skin.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair's fortune did not stop at his lapel.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans began running up to the palisade and shooting into the village through the small holes the Fijians had previously been using.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Musket fire and Congreve rockets poured into Sualib.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Americans began trickling into the village, in twos, by a narrow bridge, through the gate, and into the fort following Sinclair's example.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point Sinclair shot a chief with his pistol, which turned out to be the chief of Sualib.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Several natives carried the chiefs limp body to a nearby hut.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The battle crept on in a state of havoc for about 15–30 minutes before a Congreve rocket hit the top of a dry roof and caught fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native warrior got on to of the roof in an effort to remove the rocket before the fire spread, but he was shot down in a hail of bullets.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fire proliferated and began to engulf the village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The blaze forced the natives to flee the ditch and into American musket fire, which cut them down.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The resulting spectacle was pure pandemonium.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A translator attempted to shout that the women and children would be allowed to escape.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fire and gun smoke were everywhere, children were weeping, pigs were crying, the fire roared, the noise was ear splitting.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans cheered their success and then fell back to a coconut grove, as the village burned.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a half an hour to an hour, the fires had settled to an approachable state, the Americans reentered the village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They soon discovered, that based on the remaining native supplies, the natives had expected a lengthy engagement.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans found piles of hollowed out calabashes filled with water, burnt yams and charred pigs.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Discarded muskets, spears, and clubs littered the floor of the ditch.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The weapons were pilled up on a pyre and immolated.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After searching the still standing huts, Underwood's bloody cap was discovered.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Out of the bodies only four or five survived being burnt to ashes including a little girl and the chief of Sualib.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The preservation of the chief's cadaver was soon ended, as with a streak of vengeance, the Americans threw his body into a burning house.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Evidence of the horror that had occurred before was still present to the senses of the Americans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The treeline was pierced by misfired arrows.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The smoke filled the nostrils of the sailors and marines which took on the smell of burnt human flesh, as it approached the heavens in an otherwise blue sky.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was in this setting that the otherwise exhausted combatants decided to rest and refresh themselves on coconuts to quench their thirst.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the men drank, it was discovered that the most significant injury among them was a sailor who suffered a solitary gash on the leg from an arrow.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After the brief respite, the force divided into the marching lines to the nearby village of Arro and burned several houses and farms along the way.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was suspected that most of the surviving villagers were hiding somewhere in the hills.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, they did encounter one native on the way who was instantly bayonetted multiple times to death.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon arriving there, they found that Arro had already been burned down by Wilkes and Alden.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Adding the bayoneted man as a casualty and counting the lowest and highest estimate, approximately 58 to about 88 Fijians had been killed between Arro and Sualib.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The last skirmish that occurred during the battle lasted throughout much of the day.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After midday, Lieutenant Emmons had been tracking five canoes that had been spotted in the morning.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They had escaped Malolo, and were hiding near Malolo Lailai.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Each canoe contained about eight fighters and their sides were reinforced to curb a potential attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons was sailing his cutter which was, at this point, only at half its normal capacity.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He had only seven men under his command.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In any case, Emmons made full sail and pulled up alongside the closest canoe.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed several natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and another sailor jumped in the canoe, as Emmons grappled with a spear throwing native, the sailor killed him with a hatchet.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One canoe got away, but the natives in the other canoes jumped overboard.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After they took the plunge, they were either shot, slashed, or axed by the Americans as they swam for the shallows.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons sailed back to the *Porpoise* before midnight.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning it was discovered that the bodies of the natives killed by Emmons and his men were eaten by sharks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day (July 25, 1840) Wilkes made plans with a declaration to lead a second engagement to kill "Every man on the Island", however an assembly of natives congregated on the beach near the *Flying Fish*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes summoned an interpreter and together they sailed on a gig to shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As Wilkes drew nearer the crowd dispersed, leaving behind a lone native woman to treat with Wilkes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The native offered Wilkes some of Underwood and Henry's clothes, belongings, and a chicken as an offer of peace.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes retrieved the recovered items from his fallen crewmen, but refused the chicken.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was under the impression that according to Fijian tradition, for a nation to be truly conquered the populace of that nation must be present to witness a peace declaration.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Instead Wilkes entreated to the woman, he and his men would meet on a hill in southern Malolo to discuss peace terms with the whole tribe.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If however, the remaining chiefs and peoples of Malolo did not make an appearance, then Wilkes and his men would continue the onslaught.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Around noon, Wilkes and his men climbed the hill, which perfectly overlooked views of the sheer destruction yesterday had delivered.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, at approximately 4 P.M. a column of weeping natives (including 40 men) began to approach the hill.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At first, the native would not go beyond the foot of the hill.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes threatened to wipe them out if they did not climb the hill in an act of contrite submission.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives crawled on their hands and knees up the hill.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An old native man approached Wilkes, spoke for Malolo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He begged for mercy, and declared that his people would never attack white men again.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He admitted his people were conquered and had only about 80 surviving men left.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He also offered Wilkes two young native women in reparation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave a speech through a translator about the power of "white" people and that if a similar attack ever happened again, then he would drive the people of Malolo to extinction.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] July 26, Wilkes and his men went to what was left of Arro village and had the people fill casks of water for his vessels.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the morning of July 27, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* sailed off the coast of Arro and 70 natives loaded them with 3,000 gallons of water, 12 pigs, and 3,000 coconuts.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day the natives retrieved Underwood's pocket watch which had melted in the fire, and Henry's glasses.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 31, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* returned to Bua bay where the rest of the fleet was working.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes privately blamed Alden and Underwood for the deaths of Henry and Underwood.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In retaliation Wilkes had Underwood's possessions sold at an auction to much protest from the officers, and most notably midshipman James Blair who was the executor of Underwood's freshly written will just prior to the battle of Malolo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes vindictive streak did not appear to end with Underwood.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes next turned his anger to chief Veidovi.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From his capture up until the end of the expedition in Fiji, Hudson had been kind to Veidovi and even permitted him to go on deck and speak to the officers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes had Veidovi transferred from the *Peacock* to his flagship the *Vincennes*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now Wilkes kept Veidovi confined to quarters.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Wilkes had the ships barber cut Vincennes hair.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This mortified Veidovi, since his hair marked his status and was important in Fijian culture.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. had ended Wilkes published a book called *Narrative of the United States Exploring Expedition* in 1844.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes in hindsight was mad at Alden for a number of perceived grievances.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these grievances included the idea that Alden was responsible for the deaths of Underwood and Henry.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And he wrote about this an his other grievances in his book.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. left Fiji in August and set a course for more surveying and scientific work in Hawaii, before temporary splitting up the expedition to survey Hawaii and other islands in Polynesia such as modern day French Polynesia, the Cook Islands, and the Gilbert Islands.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, the expedition surveyed the Columbia River.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] On the return trip the expedition traveled to Wake Island, and returned by way of the Philippines, Borneo, Singapore, Polynesia, and the Cape of Good Hope, reaching New York on June 10, 1842.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While on the surveying expedition for the Columbia river, Wilkes appeared to have loosened his enmity to Veidovi at one point.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He began allowing him on the deck of the *Vincennes*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] A few months later on July 4th 1841 Wilkes and his men landed on Vancouver Island and fired off two howitzers in celebration of the holiday.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] During this occasion Veidovi was allowed to walk on shore.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The next year in June, 4th 1842 Veidovi died a few days after landing in New York (possibly from pulmonary tuberculosis), although the Washington Herald inaccurately asserted that Veidovi died from a lack of eating human meat.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Veidovi's death surgeons at the Brooklyn Naval Hospital removed Veidovi's head, pickled it, and then after a time the flesh was removed, and the skull was thereafter labeled Specimen 292 and was featured in the Smithsonian Institution, and became one of the most popular exhibits.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Wilkes' arrival in New York several court martials were organized for the entire Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes had made many enemies in both the Navy, and the government.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He was almost universally despised by his men for many of the actions he took during the expedition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Other officers were charged with various crimes, but Wilkes was charged with 11, and his actions throughout the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. were criticized in the defense of the other officers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his actions during Fiji the Battle of Malolo, Wilkes was charged with illegally attacking the natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes justified his actions by stating "But I felt then as I do now, that the punishment was sufficient and effectual, while it was accompanied, as far as it could be, with mercy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, even the most ardent of Wilkes detractors supported Wilkes on this matter.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Many of them indicated by their words and actions that they hated the natives for killing their friends and desired revenge.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] What's more, Wilkes was able to garner sympathy for the death of his nephew of which it was universally acknowledged that he loved dearly.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ultimately Wilkes was cleared of all charges including his Fiji charges.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The exception was that Wilkes was found guilty of illegally flogging marines and sailors in Hawaii after they refused to work when their enlistments were up.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As a consequence, Wilkes was given a public reprimand.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In 1843, a 22-foot cenotaph obelisk was built in Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge Massachusetts to remember the officers who had fallen in the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] More specifically, the monument memorialized the loss of life in two separate events of the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This included the loss of the USS *Sea Gull* (1838) a schooner that was Captained by Midshipman James W.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Reid with the help of Midshipman Frederick A.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The *Sea Gull* was awaiting resupply from the USS *Relief* (1836), after which she was due to rendezvous with the rest of the fleet at Valparaíso, Chile.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] She was last spotted off Cape Horn at Midnight on 28 April 1839.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] After a while when the *Sea Gull* never returned the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While one side of the obelisk commemorates the memory of the officers of the *Sea Gull*, another preserves the memory of Henry Wilkes and Joseph Underwood killed during the first day of the battle of Malolo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Officers and Scientific Corps. of the expedition took up a collection for their fallen comrades by the end of the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes and his family desired that this monument should be constructed at a cemetery in Brooklyn, New York for the benefit of Henry's mother and sister who lived near by.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, in part due to spite over Wilkes' treatment of them the officers had the monument built in Cambridge close to Underwood's widow.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Specifically the Obelisk reads: "To the memory of Lieutenant Joseph A.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Underwood and Midshipman Wilkes Henry, U.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This cenotaph is erected by their associates, the officers and scientific corps of the U.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Methodist missionary Reverend David Cargill reported to Hudson that because of the arrest of Veidovi, the other chiefs of Rewa became terrified at the prospect of harming white people.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And that this show of strength served to aid in both Western trade and missionary work.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his political, translation, and informative aid in the expedition Wilkes made David Whippey the temporary consul of the United States in Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, a more formal consul named John B.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, with Wilkes' recommendation Secretary of State John C.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Calhoun appointed him to vice consul of Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Nancy Shoemaker, she theorizes the combination of the Fijians newfound fear of retribution for attacks against Westerners following the attacks of the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.. combined with Whippey's new position of power provided a lasting impact on Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In that vein of thought, Shoemaker points out that Whippey's new found power complemented his unofficial title as chief of the white men/beachcombers of Levuka and the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] With this fusion of power came a desire for autonomy for both Whippey and the white beachcombers he represented.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Traditionally, the beachcombers were compelled to fight for whichever local chief had them under employment.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, when chief Cakobau of Bau called them up to aid in him waging war against Cakaudrove at Somosomo, the beachcombers refused.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] They claimed they wished to protect their property.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Cakobau became incensed, and was even more so after he lost the war against Cakaudrove.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He feared that directly punishing Whippey and his beachcombers might bring down the wrath of the United States or another western power.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Instead his punishment of the beachcombers was indirect and subtle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He encouraged other tribes under his domain to steal the beachcombers polygamous wives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He later demanded greater tributes from them and sent arsonists to burn down their homes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The situation became exasperated when in 1843, the beachcombers refused to participate in the Bau–Rewa war.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This time Cakobau exiled the whites and their mixed-race children to Bua and near the village of Solevu that was destroyed by the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, by 1849, Cakobau allowed the beachcombers to return to Levuka.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Trade in Levuka had suffered since the exile.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers were all to often, the most reliable middlemen traders for Fijians and the trade ships that came through Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] To Cakobau's dismay upon the beachcombers return they began to dominate all foreign trade to the exclusion of Cakobau and the Fijian people as a whole.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers under Whippey began defending themselves against small skirmishes or arsons as advanced by Cakobau.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] At this point beachcombers like Whippey, and their mixed families, had begun to transcend from being middleman minorities to autonomous settlers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers at Levuka and elsewhere gradually made moves to separate themselves from the Fijian populace and became a semi independent military and trading power.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The British would later capitalize upon this development, when they took ownership of it in 1874 and made Levuka its first capital.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, according to Shoemaker, it was the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.'s precedent for protection and subsequent retaliation for harm against whites that began the beachcombers move towards autonomy and the later British take over of the islands.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. taken as a whole led to several lasting scientific revelations, explorative discoveries, and historical preservations that continue to endure to today.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji expeditions artifacts contributed to the earliest collections for the National Institute for the Promotion of Science, the precursor to what would become the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In addition to the cannibalized skull and the skull of chief Veidovi, an assortment of Fijian weapons had been procured for future display at the institute.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes names the Ringgold Isles after Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Numerous botanical samples were also obtained from Fiji and other lands the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. surveyed, and were placed in the United States Botanic Garden or the Smithsonian Gardens.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Dried plant specimens comprised the core of what is now the **National Herbarium**, an herbarium curated by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji Expedition was also not without its merits, for its contributions to science.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As mentioned previously, Horatio Hale documented 5,600 words in the Fiji language as well as other information of anthological and cultural importance.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Through his studies he produced the book *Ethnography and Philology* (1846), which is said to have laid the foundations of the ethnography of Polynesia, including Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He is often cited as the Father of Polynesian ethnology.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Moreover, the scientists Charles Pickering, William Brackenridge, and William Rich, collectively brought over 50,000 specimens of 10,000 species.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And of the 241 charts that were created during the Ex.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. there was included the first ever complete chart of Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] In October 1855, the United States Navy sent a warship to Fiji during the civil war on the islands.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] They demanded compensation from Seru Epenisa Cakobau, the Vunivalu of Bau and self-proclaimed Tui Viti (King of Fiji), in response to the alleged arson attacks on the American commercial agent in Lautoka, Viti Levu.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] The initial incident that led to the American expedition was the burning in 1849 of the house owned by agent John Brown Williams when it was hit by cannon fire.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] A subsequent incident happened the same year as the expedition when, again, fire was to interrupt Williams's duties.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] Another accidental fire on Nukulau destroyed his store, and some Fijians looted it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] Boutwell, was sent to monitor the unrest in October, and her crew landed multiple times to protect American interests.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] When Commander Boutwell heard of the incidents involving William's house and store, he demanded US$5,000 in compensation from King Cakobau.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] This initial claim was supplemented by further claims totalling $45,000.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] He gave the natives a deadline and threatened them with a landing party of marines and sailors to capture the king in the island's village if they failed to pay.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] Fijian warriors put up some resistance, one American service man was killed, and two were wounded.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] Ultimately the Adams's men were successful in routing a contingent of natives from Lautoka, but Cakobau and the survivors escaped capture.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] Cakobau's claim to be King of Fiji was by no means universally recognised by his fellow-chiefs who jealously guarded the independence of their fiefdoms.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] If he acknowledged the debt, he did not have sufficient funds to pay it, yet if he disclaimed it by saying that it fell under the jurisdiction of another chief, he would jeopardize his claim to the kingship, which he wanted foreign powers to recognise.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] He decided to bide his time, hoping that the Americans were only bluffing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1855-fiji-expedition] An 1858 Fiji expedition, involving the crew of *Vandalia*, achieved clearer results, and the debt itself was not resolved until 1862.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] In 1858, the United States Navy launched an operation on the island of Waya in Fiji following the death of two American traders there.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The Pacific Squadron executed a punitive expedition against the native warriors of Seru Epenisa Cakobau and defeated them in a pitched battle at the village of Somatti.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] In mid-1858, two American citizens on Waya were killed and cannibalized by the natives.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] When word of the incident reached the American consulate at Ovalau, the Pacific Squadron sent the *Vandalia*, and the sloop-of-war arrived on 2 October 1858.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The *Vandalia'*s draft was not shallow enough to reach Waya, so Commander Sinclair chartered the schooner *Mechanic* and placed her under the command of veteran Lieutenant Charles Caldwell.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] A force of 10 marines, forty sailors and a 12-pounder howitzer were mustered for the landing on Waya.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] A few Fijian guides and three American merchant sailors also participated.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] One was Captain Josiah Knowles of the *Wild Wave*, a clipper ship wrecked off Oeno Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Knowles and 40 others were marooned on the island until being rescued by *Vandalia* and taken to Fiji.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The expedition left Ovalau on 6 October 1858 and sailed west around the northern end of the main island of Viti Levu to Waya.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] During their passage to the island, Lieutenant Caldwell's men heard many stories from towns and villages about the warriors of Waya.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The Wayan chiefs responsible for the deaths of the two American traders also sent a letter: "Do you suppose we have killed the two white men for nothing?
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] No, we killed them and we have eaten them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] We are great warriors, and we delight in war".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell later wrote, "...and woe to the members of any strange tribe that falls into their hands... to be clubbed to death and eaten is the only alternative for the captive.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] It is not a matter of surprise that the tribes along our route learned with feelings of satisfaction the nature of our expedition".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] At 03:00 on 9 October, the Americans made a landing and marched inland toward the village of Somatti over tropical and mountainous terrain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] While climbing through the mountains, the 12-pounder was destroyed and left behind when it fell 2,300 feet (700 m) down the side of a hill as the expedition tried to pull it up.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The column reached Somatti in daytime, and over 300 native warriors were in front of the village for defense, clothed in white robes and armed with clubs, rocks, spears, bows, and some muskets.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The Americans had swords and carbine rifles.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Lieutenant Caldwell ordered a flanking maneuver on the left side of the mass of warriors.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Routed, the natives dispersed themselves amongst the town or fled into the jungle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Bartlett, who led a group of sailors, sang "Red, White, and Blue" and let out three cheers before charging and capturing the village.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The crew of the 12-pounder, with no gun to fire, took charge of burning the village, and over 115 huts were destroyed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Marines under Lieutenant Alan Ramsey, providing a rearguard for the sailors, repulsed a final Wayan attack from the jungle after they had regrouped.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] In all fourteen warriors, including the two chiefs, were counted dead after a fierce half-hour battle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Two marines survived their wounds by musketry, two sailors were hurt badly by rocks, one other marine was hit in the leg with an arrow, and a sailor from *Wild Wave* was hurt as well.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] After the battle the Americans took until 16 October to return to the coast where the *Mechanic* was waiting.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] They stopped at friendly Fijian fishing villages and spread the news of their victory.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell noted that two ramrods and one bayonet were lost during the march, and a large amount of ammunition was used in battle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/1858-fiji-expedition] The lieutenant received much credit for the operation, considered one of the most impressive military campaigns launched by the United States in the South Pacific during the nineteenth century.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] On 3 January 2026, the United States launched a military strike in Venezuela and captured incumbent Venezuelan president Nicolás Maduro and his wife, Cilia Flores.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The US operation, codenamed **Operation Absolute Resolve**, began around 2 a.m. local time, when explosions were observed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The US Armed Forces bombed infrastructure across northern Venezuela to suppress air defenses as an apprehension force attacked Maduro's compound in Caracas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro and Flores were transported to New York City by US forces to face their trial for drug trafficking there.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The operation is sometimes considered a military conflict because seven US soldiers were injured.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] At 2 hours and 28 minutes, it qualifies as one of the shortest wars in history.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The US federal government announced that Maduro and Flores had been indicted on several charges related to narcoterrorism.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro and Flores pleaded not guilty to the charges in Manhattan federal court on 5 January 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] US president Donald Trump and his administration justified the operation as a law-enforcement action, with military support, that the president has "inherent constitutional authority" to undertake.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Venezuelan vice president Delcy Rodríguez denounced Maduro's "kidnapping".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Venezuelan officials said at least 23 Venezuelan security officers were killed during the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Cuban government said that 32 members of the Cuban military and intelligence agencies were killed.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Officials in the United Nations (UN), the US, and other countries, as well as international law experts said the raid violated the UN Charter and Venezuela's sovereignty..
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Other reactions around the world included celebrations by the Venezuelan diaspora and protests against the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Venezuelan government remained in place, with Rodríguez sworn in as acting president on 5 January 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Multiple political prisoners (including foreigners) detained in Venezuela were released, a gesture which, according to Trump, contributed to avoiding a second wave of attacks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] On 30 January, Rodríguez announced an amnesty bill for political prisoners covering the period of 1999 to present, which was approved on 19 February.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] As of 8 March, the number of political prisoners released confirmed since 8 January was 621 out of an estimate of over 800 held before January, according to human rights organizations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] By February, the US and Venezuela had already restarted diplomatic relations, with the Embassy of the United States, Caracas, being reopened for the first time since its closure in 2019.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump and his administration made clear that access to Venezuelan oil was a core reason for the action.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The US announced a 50-million-barrel oil supply deal with the remaining government in Venezuela, with the first $300 million already received on 20 January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] On 29 January, a new law was passed by Rodríguez to give private companies control over the production and sale of oil.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In parallel, the US lifted sanctions imposed on Venezuelan oil trade and issued licenses for companies to trade Venezuelan oil.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to US secretary of energy Chris Wright, who visited Venezuela in February, sales of Venezuelan oil have already reached over $1 billion since Maduro's capture and about $5 billion are expected in the upcoming months.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In June 2026, Niño Guerrero, leader of the Venezuelan criminal organization Tren de Aragua, was killed in a joint operation between Venezuela and the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Nicolás Maduro has been criticized for authoritarian rule since Hugo Chávez hand-picked him as the next president of Venezuela in 2013.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Mark Weisbrot states that Venezuela has faced an economic crisis since the oil glut of the 2010s, due to its export-dependent economy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] For years, the US government pressured Maduro, considering him an "illegitimate leader".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro's victory in the 2018 Venezuelan presidential election was disputed and 45 countries did not accept the results, causing a presidential crisis that divided the international community from 2019 to 2023.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The opposition showed evidence and vote tallies that its candidate, Edmundo González, had won a majority, matching the results of pre-election opinion polls, who was "widely believed to have won [the] election, and by a landslide", according to *The New York Times*.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Venezuelan government issued an arrest warrant for González, who left the country and was granted asylum in Spain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In January 2025, the Biden administration recognized González as Venezuela's legitimate president-elect.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Trump administration had sought to prosecute Maduro on narco-terrorism charges since at least 2020.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] At a 2023 press conference, Trump said, "Venezuela was about to collapse.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Cilia Flores is a Venezuelan lawyer and politician who rose to power after she represented Chávez, who was imprisoned following the 1992 coup attempt; Flores helped secure his release in 1994.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] She was an influential part of Chavez's movement, Chavismo, although known for keeping a low public profile.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In 2000, one year after Chavez became president of Venezuela, Flores was voted into the National Assembly.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] After becoming president of the National Assembly in 2006, she banned journalists from the legislative chamber, and was criticized for appointing dozens of relatives to public positions in Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] She was the Attorney General of Venezuela from 2012 to 2013.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Having known each other since the 1990s, Flores and Maduro married in 2013 following his succession of Chávez as president.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro, rather than describing her as the First Lady, has used the term "*primera combatiente*" or "First Combatant" of the revolution.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] US Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) officers arrested two of her nephews in a Haitian sting operation in 2015, and they were sentenced on drug conspiracy charges but released in a 2022 prisoner swap with the Biden administration that included the Citgo Six.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Flores has been sanctioned or the subject of travel bans by the United States, Canada, Panama, and Colombia for allegations of corruption and undermining democracy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Venezuela holds the world's largest proven oil reserves, estimated at 17% of the global total, or 300 billion barrels.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In December 2025, the US began a maritime blockade of sanctioned oil or shadow fleet tankers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Following the raid, Trump's press conference made clear that oil was a motivation for action in Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Citing the restructuring of Venezuela's oil industry in 1976 and 2007, Trump, Stephen Miller, and others claimed that Venezuela had stolen oil from US companies.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump suggested on 5 January that seized oil could be treated as a US asset, asserting the willingness to sell it or add it to the US Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Trump administration also expressed interest in Venezuela's large deposits of gold and rare earth minerals.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Some experts noted that the Maduro government had previously attempted to offer the US access to these minerals in a failed attempt to stave off military action, with the ongoing operations marking a return to "resource imperialism".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] ExxonMobil and ConocoPhillips left Venezuela after their assets were expropriated in 2007, while Chevron continued its operations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Unlike Congress, Trump claimed to have spoken with oil companies both "before and after".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The United States accused Maduro of electoral fraud and presiding over a "narco-state".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In March 2020, during Trump's first term, the United States Justice Department indicted Maduro on cocaine-trafficking conspiracy charges, which Maduro denied.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump designated two Venezuelan drug gangs, the Tren de Aragua and the Cartel of the Suns, as Foreign Terrorist Organizations (FTOs) in January and July 2025 respectively, and alleged that the latter was led by Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro denied being involved in cartel leadership and characterized the designations as an attempt to use the war on drugs for regime change.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Some Latin American crime experts have described the Cartel of the Suns as more of a general network of Venezuelan government and military corruption than as an organized group.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Also in July 2025, a secret order instructed the US military to use force against cartels listed as terrorist organizations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] But we are in a transition to stabilization phase.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In August 2025, the United States began a military buildup in the southern Caribbean, deploying warships and military personnel.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) sent a team into Venezuela that began tracking Maduro's movements, using a source close to the Venezuelan president, and plans were made for the capture of Maduro months in advance.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Delta Force and other participants in the operation erected a mockup of the safe house in which Maduro was believed to be hiding, described by Trump as a "very highly guarded ... fortress".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In September, the United States Southern Command began conducting military strikes on vessels in the Caribbean Sea, alleging some were trafficking drugs on behalf of Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In November 2025, Venezuelan opposition leader María Corina Machado promised to open Venezuela's oil and gas reserves during a business meeting in Miami attended by Trump, and the Trump administration engaged in secret talks with Maduro's government about its oil reserves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In December 2025, this escalated to include seizures of sanctioned oil tankers carrying Venezuelan crude.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] These seizures formed part of the broader blockade on sanctioned oil preceding the January 2026 operation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The US also launched covert operations in Venezuela under the directive of the CIA in late December.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] On 2 January 2026, Trump announced that the US military would conduct strikes inside Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In the weeks preceding the operation, Trinidad and Tobago signed an agreement with the US to allow US military access to its airports.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] General Dan Caine, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said in a 3 January press conference that the US military had spent months planning and rehearsing the operation, with forces positioned and ready by early December.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In late December, the US escalated its military efforts against Venezuela onto land, including striking a remote northern port reportedly used by Tren de Aragua for smuggling.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] At that time, Maduro rejected an offer from the US to go into exile in Turkey.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] President Trump stated that the operation had been ready to launch several days earlier but was postponed due to poor weather and cloud cover, which made flying into Caracas hazardous.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] General Caine, added that US forces waited for conditions to improve to minimize the risk to civilian populations and explained that the mission proceeded only after the weather "broke just enough" to allow aircraft to maneuver safely into position.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Venezuelan proposals were made to US envoy Richard Grenell through Qatari channels; the Trump administration reportedly rejected the overtures.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to the *Financial Times*, Delcy Rodríguez's brother Jorge Rodríguez had held talks with the United States government in 2025 to have his sister lead a post-Maduro transitional government, though those talks had included Maduro being allowed to go into exile instead of being captured.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Anonymous sources speaking for *The Guardian* said that Delcy and Jorge Rodríguez were communicating with the American and Qatar officials.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to US Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen Dan Caine, Trump gave the order to proceed at 23:46 VET (22:46 EST) on 2 January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The administration did not notify the United States Congress in advance of the strikes, saying they had concerns that this could endanger the mission.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to Semafor, *The New York Times* and *The Washington Post* knew about the strikes before they were carried out.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] At least seven explosions were reported at around 02:00 VET (01:00 EST) on 3 January, and low-flying aircraft were seen, predominantly in La Guaira, Higuerote, Meseta de Mamo, Baruta, El Hatillo, Charallave, and Carmen de Uria, most of which are in or near the capital city Caracas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The operation involved 150 aircraft from the United States Navy, Air Force, and Marine Corps.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump said the United States "had a fighter jet for every possible situation".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Following the operation, White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt shared an eyewitness account of Venezuelan military personnel suffering injuries consistent with sonic weaponry during the American strike.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump later told Katie Pavlich that "we have weapons nobody else knows about [...] we have some amazing weapons.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The operation reportedly used one-way attack drones, which is believed to be the first such operational usage by the US military.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Most of the explosions targeted antennas and active military bases.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Early reports suggested that the explosions were at Generalissimo Francisco de Miranda Air Base (La Carlota) and Fort Tiuna, two military installations in Caracas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Large explosions were also reported at Higuerote Airport, on the Venezuelan coast.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Helicopters from the 160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment carried Delta Force soldiers into Caracas with air cover provided by the fighters and bombers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] One helicopter was damaged by Venezuelan ground defenses but continued on its mission.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) personnel, including the Hostage Rescue Team, accompanied the military to formally arrest Maduro at his compound.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Smoke was seen rising from one military hangar in a Caracas base, while another was left unpowered.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The strikes happened under the cover of darkness as a result of both the timing of the operation and the US military's disruption of power in the city of Caracas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Multiple shipping containers were destroyed and damaged in the La Guaira port strikes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Satellite imagery from Vantor showed at least five destroyed warehouses, burned vehicles, and a blown-up security post.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] An aircraft, believed to be a Beechcraft Baron, and a Buk-M2E surface-to-air missile system were destroyed at Higuerote Airport.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Venezuelan Science and Technology Minister Gabriela Jiménez Ramírez shared footage on social media of crumbled buildings of the Venezuelan Institute for Scientific Research (IVIC) in La Guaira which she attributed to strikes of AGM-154 glide bombs by the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Venezuelan government said that Maduro declared a national state of emergency after the explosions began.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The Venezuelan government promised to defend against US military actions which it accused of seeking regime change.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] It described them as "imperialist aggression" and called for the United Nations Security Council (UNSC) to be convened.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] At 05:21 Venezuelan Standard Time (VET) or 04:21 Eastern Standard Time (ET), Trump announced that Maduro and Flores had been captured and flown out of the country.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The capture was undertaken by the US Army's Delta Force, with on-the-ground intelligence provided by the CIA.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump posted a photograph on his Truth Social account of Maduro on board USS *Iwo Jima*, showing him blindfolded, with soundproof headphones and a gray Nike sweatsuit, holding a plastic water bottle.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to US Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Maduro was "arrested" and would face criminal charges in the US.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Nahum Fernández, leader of the ruling United Socialist Party of Venezuela, said Maduro and Flores were captured at Fort Tiuna; they reportedly slept at multiple locations and had a "fortress-like" compound at Fort Tiuna.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Delcy Rodríguez confirmed that both Maduro and Flores were missing and demanded confirmation they were alive via an audio message on state television.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to Reuters sources, Rodríguez was in Russia on 3 January 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] While other rumors indicate she was vacationing in Margarita Island.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Other reports indicated that Rodríguez was in Caracas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Shortly before 18:00 VET (17:00 EST), the airplane carrying Maduro and Flores landed at Stewart Air National Guard Base in New York.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] He was seen walking off the jet, surrounded by federal agents, before entering a hangar.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] He was then flown by helicopter to the Westside Heliport in Manhattan, New York City and then taken by an armored convoy to a local Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) field office where he was processed before ultimately being held in the Metropolitan Detention Center Brooklyn.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Hours after the capture, the United States attorney general Pam Bondi announced that Maduro and Flores had been indicted in the Southern District of New York on charges related to "narcoterrorism".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The indictment listed the charges as narco-terrorism conspiracy, cocaine importation conspiracy, possession of machine guns and destructive devices, and conspiracy to possess machine guns and destructive devices.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The amended indictment did not refer to the Cartel of the Suns as an organized group as previously alleged by the US, but instead as a corrupt patronage system, which aligns with experts' descriptions of its operations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro and his wife were arraigned in a Manhattan federal court on 5 January 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Before pleading, Maduro said: "I am the president of Venezuela, I consider myself a prisoner of war.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] I was captured at my home in Caracas." Both pleaded not guilty to numerous drug trafficking charges.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] US District Judge Alvin Hellerstein ordered that Maduro be held until at least a 17 March hearing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] However, this court appearance would later be delayed to 26 March 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Maduro and Flores would return to court as scheduled on 26 March 2026, and would afterwards be transferred back to jail in Brooklyn.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Venezuelan defense minister Vladimir Padrino López said that US combat helicopters fired rockets and missiles in urban areas and that officials were working to gather information on the number of fatalities and injuries.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Padrino López also stated that most of Maduro's personal guard were killed during the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] *The New York Times* reported on 3 January 2026 that an anonymous Venezuelan official said at least 40 people, including civilians and military personnel, were killed in the attack, updated to 80 on 4 January, "according to a senior Venezuelan official".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Independent Venezuelan journalistic reports confirmed that most Venezuelan dead were among members of the presidential guard, with two civilian deaths.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The presence of Cuban troops in Venezuela was made public after the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Their presence was denied as far back as 2008.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In 2019 Maduro had claimed in an interview that no Cuban military personnel were stationed in the country and that his personal guard was Venezuelan.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Trump indicated that Cuban forces were involved in the operation, stating: "You know, a lot of Cubans were killed yesterday." The government of Cuba reported that 32 Cubans were killed in Venezuela, all members of armed forces and intelligence services.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] One of the most senior Cuban soldiers that died, Colonel Humberto Roca, was responsible for Fidel Castro's security in the past.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to Reuters reporting in February, anonymous Venezuelan officials indicated that some Cuban security forces and medical doctors in Venezuela were returning to Cuba, diminishing their role in Venezuelan politics.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to some officials, Cubans were being removed from their posts in Venezuela's General Directorate of Military Counterintelligence (DGCIM).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] On 6 January 55 military deaths were confirmed: the victims were 32 Cubans and 23 Venezuelans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Both the countries released on the same day the identities of the killed soldiers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Also on 6 January, military forces posted a video on social media in honor of 24 soldiers killed during the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Attorney General Tarek William Saab indicated that dozens of military personnel and civilians were killed and the total number is still under investigation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] A day later, Diosdado Cabello said that 100 persons died during the bombing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Independent monitors reported as of 7 January Venezuelan military casualties as of 6 January of 42 or 43 soldiers (mostly at Fort Tiuna), in addition to the 32 Cuban military personnel, and 2 civilians.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] On 16 January, Venezuelan defense minister Vladimir Padrino López, said that 47 soldiers, including 9 women, were killed during the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Acting president Delcy Rodríguez declared seven days of mourning for the soldiers killed during the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The remains of the Cuban fatalities were repatriated on 15 January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] They received a mass funeral ceremony in Havana upon arrival.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] In Catia La Mar, strikes hit a three-story civilian apartment complex, killing one person, seriously injuring another, and destroying the exterior wall.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Yohana Rodríguez Sierra, a Colombian citizen, was reported as a civilian fatality in El Hatillo.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The US had been bombing nearby telecommunications antennas, according to the victim's relative.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] According to the Department of Defense, seven US soldiers were injured and expected to survive.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] The soldiers suffered shrapnel and gunfire wounds.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] During the 2026 State of the Union Address, Trump awarded the Medal of Honor to Chief Warrant Officer Eric Slover, one of the helicopter pilots that got injured during the operation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Slover was the lead Chinook pilot for the air assault element of the operation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] His helicopter came under fire as the flight approached Maduro's compound, and he was hit in the leg and hip by four bullets.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] His aircraft was also hit but remained flyable.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] Despite his wounds, Slover maintained control of the aircraft and got the Delta Team onboard over the compound and allowed them to fast rope to the ground.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p01] He then flew back to the USS Iwo Jima located in the Caribbean Sea.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The government formerly led by Maduro remained in place.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Vice President Delcy Rodríguez described Maduro as Venezuela's "only president" and called for calm and unity to defend the country amid what she called his "kidnapping".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] She stated that Venezuela would "never again be a colony of any empire".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 3 January 2026, the Supreme Tribunal of Justice ordered Rodríguez to assume the interim presidency due to Maduro's absence.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The Venezuelan military announced it would recognize Rodríguez as acting president and called for a return to normalcy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Rodríguez was sworn in as acting president of Venezuela on 5 January 2026 by her brother and president of the National Assembly of Venezuela, Jorge Rodríguez.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The US Federal Aviation Administration issued a notice to airmen on 3 January 2026 prohibiting US aircraft from operating within Venezuelan airspace, citing "ongoing military activity".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The US Embassy in Caracas issued a shelter-in-place order from its relocated operations in Colombia.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The southern area of Caracas reportedly lost power.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Republican Senator Mike Lee said that Secretary of State Marco Rubio "anticipates no further action in Venezuela now that Maduro is in US custody," and that Maduro was expected to go on trial in the US.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] In a television interview with ABC News, Rubio thanked news organizations who had received leaks about the operation before it took place for not reporting on it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] According to *Semafor*, *The New York Times* and *The Washington Post* had received information about the attack but did not report on it in order to not endanger the lives of US personnel involved in the operation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The acknowledgment of the media withholding information about the operation came after defense secretary Pete Hegseth imposed strict restrictions on Pentagon reporters due to a mistrust of journalists' abilities to withhold militarily sensitive information from the public.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 5 January 2026, the Venezuelan government issued an emergency order to police to arrest anyone who supported the US attack and mobilized *colectivos* (pro-government paramilitaries) who established roadblocks and searched cars and people.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Fourteen journalists were detained, but 13 of them were later released.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 6 January, gunfire broke out in Caracas as the ministry of communication announced that police fired upon one of their own military drones "flying without permission" but that the drone suffered no damage.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 3 January 2026, Trump stated: "We are going to run the country until such time as we can do a safe, proper and judicious transition".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] He indicated that the US might send troops to Venezuela as part of this.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Media outlets noted Rodríguez's statements contradicted Trump's.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] He also expressed openness to a US occupation of Venezuela, stating it would not cost the US anything because it would be reimbursed through revenue from Venezuela's oil reserves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 7 January, Trump stated that US efforts to revitalize Venezuela could take "much longer" than a year, adding that the Venezuelan authorities were doing "everything that we feel is necessary".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Regarding the reward the US government offered for information leading to Maduro's capture, Rubio added that nobody will be receiving it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Rubio said "I guess we save $50 million" to which Trump replied "Don't let anybody claim it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 4 January 2026, Marco Rubio retracted Trump's comments of the day before, saying the US would not govern Venezuela, but would continue to enforce the existing oil quarantine in order to pressure Venezuela for policy changes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Rubio also affirmed that the US did not officially recognize Rodríguez's presidency, despite Trump's avowal that he would work with Rodríguez.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] For her part, Rodríguez conveyed an offer to collaborate with US officials "within the framework of international law".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Of Rodríguez, Trump said that "she's cooperating", threatened her if she did not, and maintained that he would demand "total access" by US oil interests.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 7 January, Marco Rubio stated that the US government has a three-stage plan for Venezuela: stability, recovery, then transition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Trump stated there was an agreement by Venezuela to deliver a few months' worth of oil to the US, intimating that other steps, such as the freeing of political detainees and a role for the exiled opposition, might be next.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] However, President Rodríguez denied the existence of a deal, saying "no external agent" was dictating her decisions.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 8 January, the US Senate voted 52 to 47 to advance a war resolution that aimed to block the president's use of the US military to engage in military action within or against Venezuela unless authorized by Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The measure passed with the support of five Republican senators, but did not reach a veto-proof majority.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] After the announcement of the release of political prisoners by the Venezuelan government on 8 January, the US and Venezuela began discussions to restart diplomatic relations, including the possibility of reopening the United States embassy in Caracas which was closed in 2019.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] US officials visited Caracas and on 10 January, the US State Department published a security alert urging its citizens to leave Venezuela immediately due to the presence of *colectivos* (pro-government paramilitary groups) targeting US citizens.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Donald Trump announced on 14 January that he had talked by phone with acting president of Venezuela Delcy Rodríguez on oil, trade and national security.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The call was confirmed by Rodríguez, who qualified the phone call as positive.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Rodríguez also announced to have sent envoys to meet with United States officials the next day.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 15 January, Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) director John Ratcliffe met with Delcy Rodríguez in Caracas to discuss cooperation and economic stability.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] According to a US official "The director made clear Venezuela can no longer provide support to drug traffickers like TDA" (referring to the criminal organization Tren de Aragua).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] After a discussion with Delcy Rodríguez on 29 January, Trump announced the re-opening of Venezuelan airspace.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] US diplomat Laura Farnsworth Dogu was appointed chargé d'affaires for Venezuela on 22 January, and arrived to Venezuela on 30 January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] United States Energy Secretary Chris Wright arrived to Caracas on 11 February to make an assessment on Venezuela's oil industry.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] He met with Delcy Rodríguez in the presidential palace.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Days before, Wright said he was expecting to "visit some of the nation's oil fields to see firsthand how President Trump's historic US-Venezuela Energy Deal is unleashing peace and prosperity." According to the Venezuelan information minister, they discussed a bilateral energy agenda.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The last US Energy Secretary that visited Venezuela before that was Bill Richardson in 2001 under US president Bill Clinton.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Dogu and Plasencia received a US shipment of six metric tons of medicine and medical supplies that arrived in Venezuela on 13 February.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Dogu indicated it was "the first of many donations" that will arrive "in the coming days".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] When asked by reporters on 13 February, Trump said that he was "going to make a visit to Venezuela" but did not provide more details.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On February 19, the chief of the United States Southern Command, General Francis L.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Donovan, and senior Pentagon official Joseph Humire met with Delcy Rodríguez, Venezuelan defense minister Vladimir Padrino López and interior minister Diosdado Cabello in Caracas to discuss security.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] US Interior Secretary Doug Burgum visited Venezuela and met with Delcy Rodríguez on 4 March.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] They discussed the supply chains for critical minerals in Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 5 March, the US State Department and Venezuelan authorities agreed to re-establish diplomatic and consular ‌relations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 12 March, the United States declared in court that they recognized Delcy Rodríguez as the sole head of state of Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Two days later, the flag of the United States was raised for the first time in seven years at the Embassy of the United States, Caracas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 30 March, the United States reopened its embassy in Venezuela, meaning resumption of US diplomatic operations in Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 30 April, direct commercial flights between the United States and Venezuela were resumed after a seven-year suspension.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Influenced by a CIA analysis, Trump stated after the strikes that María Corina Machado, the leader of the opposition, did not have the necessary support or respect in the country to govern.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Machado confirmed on 6 January that she had no contact with Trump since October 2025 when she was announced as the Nobel winner, and voiced discontent with Trump's decision to back Rodríguez, saying she was "nothing like a moderate" and that the US expected her to take steps toward democracy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Machado dubbed Rodríguez "one of the main architects ... of repression", saying everyone was familiar with her record; she also insisted that she "absolutely" qualified for the leadership of the country and lauded Trump's "leadership and courage" in taking out Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 15 January, María Corina Machado met privately with Donald Trump and later with multiple US senators.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Machado presented her Nobel Medal to Donald Trump as a way to sway him to give the opposition a role in determining Venezuela's future.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Machado has plans to go back to Venezuela as soon as possible.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] She said that "This has nothing to do with tension or relations between Delcy Rodriguez and myself," and discussed that the "criminal structure" that has dominated Venezuela for years would eventually dismantle itself.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] A week later, Trump said he was considering involving Machado in his plans on Venezuela in some way, without specifying which role she would play.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 26 January, after a hearing on Venezuela on the US Senate, Marco Rubio met with Machado.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] She later said to reporters that a change in Venezuela was coming.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Venezuelan TV network Venevisión broadcast Machado message after meeting with Rubio.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] According to the Venezuelan national press workers union, the state regulator later cut Venevision's access to some satellite TV providers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] At Machado's request, she met for a second time with Donald Trump in the White House on 6 March to review plans for her trip to come back to Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Jorge Rodríguez announced on 8 January 2026 that an "important" number of political prisoners would be released as a "gesture" by the government.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Of an estimated 800 political prisoners in Venezuela, nine prisoners were released that day.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The US had previously requested the release of political prisoners, and Trump declared in an interview "they've been great ...
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Everything we've wanted, they've given us." Trump announced on 9 January that he had cancelled a second wave of attacks due to cooperation and the release of political prisoners.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Local NGOs reported that those released weren't "free", as they remained subject to restrictions and trial.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 23 January, Foro Penal confirmed 154 political prisoners released since 8 January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The same day, Delcy Rodríguez announced 626 prisoners released without providing a specific date.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] She called for the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights, led by Volker Türk to verify the lists.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 30 January, Delcy Rodríguez announced a general amnesty bill covering the "entire period of political violence from 1999 to the present", dating back to when Hugo Chávez first assumed his presidency.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] People convicted of murder, drug trafficking, corruption or human rights violations will not qualify under the amnesty law.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The measure was long requested by the US-backed Venezuelan opposition.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Opposition leader María Corina Machado said that the bill was not taken "voluntarily, but rather in response to pressure from the US government".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Rodríguez also announced the shutdown of El Helicoide prison, which she said would be transformed into a cultural and sport center.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Independent organizations have documented many cases of torture and human rights violation in El Helicoide.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Family of some of the prisoners gathered outside El Helicoide chanting "Freedom!".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Venezuelan opposition politician and ally of Machado, Juan Pablo Guanipa, was released from prison on 8 February but taken by unknown armed groups hours later; by February 10, his family confirmed he was under house arrest in Maracaibo, calling the measure unjust detention.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On February 19, the amnesty law was approved by the National Assembly of Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Jorge Rodríguez said that over 1557 request liberty a day after.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Juan Pablo Guanipa was also released from house arrest.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] During the 2026 State of the Union Address, Trump invited Venezuelan politician Enrique Márquez, who was imprisoned in 2025 and was released in early January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 14 January, the United States Department of Energy announced that the United States had completed their first sales of Venezuelan oil valued at $500 million as part of a $2 billion deal between United States and Venezuela governments.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] She announced the money will go to the exchange market in Venezuela, the national banks and the central bank.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Reuters indicated that the remaining $200 million were returned on 3 February according to anonymous United States officials.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The proceeds from the sales were deposited in a Qatari bank account, preventing Venezuela's creditors from seizing them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Democrats questioned the legality of this arrangement, and criticized the lack of transparency in routing the funds.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 23 January, the first cargo of 460,000 barrels of naphtha by Vitol, necessary to deal with the heavy crude oil, arrived to Venezuela in a deal with the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Before that last cargo was received in December 2025 by Chevron Corporation in an agreement with the United States as the naval blockade had stopped many suppliers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On 28 January, Delcy Rodríguez announced that the United States was unfreezing various funds related to 2019 oil sanctions on Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The next day, Reuters announced that an US refiner, Citgo, bought Venezuelan oil for the first time since 2019.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Rodríguez signed the hydrocarbon reform into law on 29 January.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The law allows private and foreign companies to operate oil projects under contracts over production and sales, lowers certain taxes, expands the oil ministry's authority, and permits asset transfers and outsourcing.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Proposals by opposition lawmakers on grant transparency and require National Assembly approval for oil contracts were rejected.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Oil industry workers participated in a demonstration to celebrate the bill approval.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The law reverted 2006 oil industry changes by Hugo Chávez to make state company PDVSA the main stakeholder in all oil projects.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] In parallel, the US Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets Control lifted various oil-related sanctions imposed on Venezuela, authorizing US companies to buy, sell, transport, store and refine Venezuelan crude oil.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] US sanctions on production of oil were not lifted.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Trump administration also announced that additional sanctions will be lifted soon.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] More sanctions were eased on 13 February, with the issue of two licenses allowing international companies to operate oil and gas projects in Venezuela and to negotiate contracts.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Payments go to a US-controlled foreign government deposit fund.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] US energy secretary that visited the Venezuela in February, said that oil sales have hit $1 billion since January and would hit another $5 billion in months.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The US Treasury Department indicated that companies working of Venezuelan oil trade have to pay local taxes, permits and fees to the government of Venezuela, while royalties and federal taxes must be paid into a fund managed by the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] According to the Reuters in February, the Venezuelan oil ministry cancelled 19 contracts with private companies on oil and gas in Venezuela signed under the government of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Venezuelan and US administrations are reviewing the credentials of the companies that signed them.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] In March, the United States issued a license to authorize the trade of Venezuelan gold and allow deals with Minarven, Venezuela's state-owned gold mining company.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] The Supreme Court ruled that his absence was temporary, not permanent.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Nicolás Maduro Guerra, Venezuelan congressman and son of Nicolás Maduro, declared on 27 January that elections in Venezuela are "not on the table" as his father was "kidnapped".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On the US Senate hearing on 28 January, US secretary of state Marco Rubio was questioned about Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] When discussing the goal of the intervention he answered "What's the end state?
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] In an interview for *Politico* in February, Machado said that she had not spoken with Trump about elections in Venezuela, but she estimated that with manual voting an election could be held in 9 to 10 months.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Maduro's industry minister Alex Saab, released from the United States in 2023 in a prisoners exchange with Venezuela, was dismissed from his role on 16 January by acting president Delcy Rodríguez.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] She merged the industry and the commerce ministry.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] According to US officials, Saab and the head of the Globovisión TV network Raúl Gorrín were arrested in February by Bolivarian National Intelligence Service (SEBIN) in a joint operation between Venezuela and the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] They are expected to be extradited to the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Venezuelan government announced on 16 May that Saab was deported to the United States.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] He is a possible witness against the prosecution of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] On April 23, 2026, U.S Army Master Sergeant Gannon Ken Van Dyke was arrested for allegedly placing more than US$33,300 in bets on the prediction site Polymarket based around whether or not Maduro would be "out by January 31, 2026" ("out" likely meaning removed from office).
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] When the bets were successful, Van Dyke gained more than US$409,000 in winnings.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] According to the Justice Department, Van Dyke was involved in the planning and execution of the operation to capture Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Van Dyke entered a not guilty plea on April 28, 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] In June 2026, a military operation was carried to kill Héctor Rusthenford Guerrero Flores, known as Niño Guerrero, the leader of the Venezuelan criminal gang Tren de Aragua.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] US president Donald Trump announced that Guerrero was killed in a airstrike on 12 June in Venezuela conducted in coordination with Venezuelan authorities.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p02] Venezuelan officials confirmed their participation in the operation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Before Maduro's capture, the Venezuelan government said it rejected and denounced the military aggression, and issued a public statement blaming the US government for the strikes, which it attributed to a plan to seize Venezuelan resources, particularly oil reserves.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Defense Minister Vladimir Padrino López stated that the attacks were illegal.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] He also said that Venezuela would resist foreign troops and that the government had declared a "state of external commotion", a type of state of emergency, following "Maduro's orders".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Vice President Delcy Rodríguez stated that Venezuela "will never again be anyone's colony – neither of old empires, nor of new empires, nor of empires in decline".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] She argued that the "war on drugs" was a pretext, claiming the United States' true objective was regime change and control of the country's "energy, mineral and natural resources".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Rodríguez also referred to the US attack on Venezuela as "Zionist".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Unitary Platform politician María Corina Machado published a statement from exile, saying that "what had to happen" for the opposition to take up the mandate they claimed from the 2024 presidential election "is happening".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] She also said the presidency should be assumed by Edmundo González, who received a majority of the vote in the 2024 presidential election, according to international observers and election-watchers.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] González said the opposition was ready to "rebuild our nation" and that the next few hours would be "decisive".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Machado, who won the 2025 Nobel Peace Prize, offered to share her award with Trump, calling the United States strike as "historic" and thanking him on behalf of the Venezuelan people.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The Nobel Prize Committee rejected her request and clarified that the prize "cannot be revoked, shared or transferred".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] According to Trump, the US would "run" Venezuela until there is a "safe, proper and judicious transition".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump went on to say that the US and US companies would seize Venezuelan oil and sell it to other countries.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump said the US would be "very strongly involved" in the Venezuelan oil industry, and that US oil companies would invest billions of dollars in the energy sector of the country.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth said "We are going to get American companies in there" to invest in the Venezuelan oil industry, resulting in "access to additional wealth and resources" for the US.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The government also indicated that American oil companies would have to invest in rebuilding Venezuelan oil infrastructure as a prerequisite for being compensated for previous asset seizures by the Venezuelan government since the first nationalization nearly 50 years ago.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Vice President JD Vance stated that the operation was justified as Maduro was wanted in the US.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] He also declared that "the stolen oil must be returned".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Florida Senators Rick Scott and Ashley Moody, along with Representative Carlos Gimenez, held a press conference in Doral praising the capture of Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Scott, who said he received a phone call from Secretary of State Marco Rubio early Saturday morning, also praised Venezuelan opposition leader María Corina Machado for her role in the events.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Democratic senator Brian Schatz, a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, warned against any US military involvement in Venezuela, saying that the United States has "no vital national interests in Venezuela to justify war".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Democratic senator Ruben Gallego said "this war is illegal".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Democratic senator Tim Kaine condemned the actions and called on Congress to support his resolution to block the use of the armed forces against Venezuela unless authorized by Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Senator Bernie Sanders also condemned the strikes, citing a risk of global instability and accusing Trump of bypassing Congress to get the country into war.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Former vice president Kamala Harris criticized the strikes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The mayor of New York City, Zohran Mamdani, said he called Trump earlier that day to express his opposition to the strikes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In a 3 January 2026 editorial, *The New York Times* editorial board condemned the attack as "dangerous and illegal", describing it as an act of "latter-day imperialism" which lacked "any semblance of international legitimacy, valid legal authority or domestic endorsement".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The AFL-CIO condemned the attack, calling it unconstitutional.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In January 2026, First Secretary of the Communist Party of Cuba Miguel Díaz-Canel strongly condemned strikes in Venezuela and the subsequent capture of President Nicolás Maduro, labeling the actions as "state terrorism".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] On 15 January 2026, he was present, alongside 94-year-old former Cuban leader Raúl Castro, in a ceremony in Havana to pay tribute to 32 Cuban soldiers killed in the United States intervention in Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump set his sights on a number of countries in the following days.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump signaled an eagerness to apply pressure on Colombia and said when asked that a similar operation there "sounds good to me".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump threatened Colombia's president Gustavo Petro, saying he has "cocaine mills and cocaine factories" and "likes making cocaine and selling it to the United States" but would not be doing it much longer.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump had recently sanctioned the Colombian leader for his alleged reluctance to combat drug trafficking in the country.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Petro promised to take up arms if he had to, and Colombia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement opposing "an undue interference" in domestic politics.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump threatened Mexico and Cuba, saying the two nations needed to do more to earn US favor, but said the latter might "fall" without US interference; he also expressed hope that Mexico would act on its own.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In an appearance on *Hannity* Trump said that "We are going to start now hitting land with regard to the cartels.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] *Newsweek* noted that Trump had said land strikes were imminent before, but also that he had been doing the groundwork by designating cartels Foreign Terrorist Organizations.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump also warned that Iran "would be hit very hard" if more demonstrators were killed during the protests occurring in the country.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump renewed his talk of annexing Greenland, an autonomous territory of the Kingdom of Denmark, with CNBC noting that this prompted more serious concerns in the wake of Maduro's capture.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The US already operates a military base in Greenland, Pituffik Space Base, and Denmark has indicated its openness to a heightened US military presence there, but Trump has been uninterested in anything less than a full US takeover, noting "that's what I feel is psychologically needed for success.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] I think that ownership gives you a thing that you can't do with, you're talking about a lease or a treaty.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Ownership gives you things and elements that you can't get from just signing a document" and "When we own it, we defend it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] You don't defend leases the same way, you have to own it".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Trump emphasized the acquisition of Greenland by the US "from the standpoint of national security".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In the following days Trump said the US is "going to do something [there] whether they like it or not", that "We're not going to have Russia or China occupy Greenland.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] That's what they're going to do if we don't.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] So we're going to be doing something with Greenland, either the nice way or the more difficult way" and "I would like to make a deal, you know, the easy way.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Following the strikes, Venezuela's neighbors acted to contain fallout.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Colombian president Gustavo Petro ordered the mobilization of security forces along the Colombia–Venezuela border in anticipation of a mass influx of Venezuelan refugees.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] On 5 January 2026, Petro, who was a former guerrilla fighter, warned that he would "take up arms" for his country if necessary after the US threatened him and his government, stating that any similar interventions in Colombia would have a response.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] On 8 January, thousands of Colombians protested against the intervention and the capture of Maduro, including the city of Cúcuta, near the Venezuelan border.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] On 10 January, the head of the largest FARC dissidents group, Nestor Gregorio Vera, called for other guerrilla groups to unite to face any US intervention.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Police in Trinidad and Tobago, which hosts the largest per-capita population of Venezuelan refugees and migrants, cordoned off key areas of the capital, Port of Spain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The government of Trinidad and Tobago, which has hosted US military personnel and vessels amid its recent buildup in the Caribbean Sea, stated that it did not participate in the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The government of Guyana, whose ongoing border dispute with Venezuela heated up in 2023–2024, had a muted response but were broadly supportive of the removal of Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Guyanese president Irfaan Ali announced that the country's security forces were "fully mobilised" to deal with potential refugees and an increase in instability along the border.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The Cuban government declared two days of national mourning on 5 and 6 January 2026 for its soldiers killed in the attacks.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Later on 16 January, tens of thousands of Cubans gathered in the José Martí Anti-Imperialist Platform outside the US embassy in Havana to demonstrate against US actions in Venezuela, the killings of 32 Cuban officers in the attack, and to demand the release of Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] On 10 January, Nicaraguan authorities arrested over 60 people for supporting the capture of Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] UN Secretary-General António Guterres stated that US actions had "worrying implications for the region", "constitute[d] a dangerous precedent", and worried "that the rules of international law have not been respected".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] He called on all Venezuelan actors to engage in an inclusive and democratic dialogue, stating "I welcome and am ready to support all efforts aimed at assisting Venezuelans in finding a peaceful way forward".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] At the request of China, Colombia, and Russia, the UNSC convened on 5 January 2026 to discuss the situation.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Representatives of Russia and China called for the immediate release of President Maduro while the US representative rejected characterizations of US actions as military aggression, describing the operation as a targeted law enforcement measure to arrest an indicted fugitive.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The attack was condemned by other countries, including Brazil, Chile, China, France, Iran, Mexico, North Korea, Russia, Slovakia, South Africa, and Spain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Government leaders in Argentina, France, Germany, Israel, Peru, and Ukraine praised the developments.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] French president Emmanuel Macron initially expressed joy, declaring on social media that "Maduro is a dictator, and his departure is good news for Venezuelans.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] He confiscated the freedom of his people and stole the 2024 elections." However, days later he nuanced his message, saying that the method employed by the Americans "does not have the support or approval" of France.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] United Kingdom prime minister Keir Starmer said that he was happy for the fall of Maduro, and he would wait to know the facts before commenting further.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Spanish prime minister Pedro Sánchez urged de-escalation, stating that "[i]nternational law and the principles of the U.N.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Charter must be respected"; this was echoed by European Union (EU) foreign policy chief and European Commission vice-president Kaja Kallas.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Several international trade union organizations, including the International Trade Union Confederation, Trade Union Confederation of the Americas, and the World Federation of Trade Unions, condemned the attack.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Environmental NGOs, including Greenpeace and Oil Change International, have criticised the United States' oil-motivated actions in Venezuela and reiterated calls for a just transition away from fossil fuels.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The Federal Council of Switzerland decided to freeze any assets held in the country by Nicolás Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Following Maduro's capture, demonstrations celebrating his removal and opposing his presidency occurred in Caracas, the capital and largest city of Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Venezuelans living abroad celebrated Maduro's removal across the United States, Spain, and Latin America.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In Doral, Florida, where the largest population of Venezuelans in the US live, Venezuelans filled the streets waving flags, singing, and chanting "freedom".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Thousands of Venezuelans celebrated Maduro's fall in Madrid, Spain.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Videos from the Colombian border city of Cúcuta showed crowds filling the streets on the night of 3 January 2026, dancing to music and chanting slogans like "virtue" and "a free Venezuela".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Similar celebrations by Venezuelan expatriates and refugees took place in Buenos Aires in Argentina, Lima in Peru, Quito in Ecuador, and Santiago in Chile.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Maduro's supporters protested against his capture in Caracas, with protesters holding portraits of Maduro and pro-Maduro and pro-*Partido Socialista Unido de Venezuela* (PSUV) banners.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] PSUV called for citizens to demand the release of Maduro and Flores.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] CNN reported that while some Venezuelans celebrated Maduro's ousting, others were skeptical of Trump's motives and condemned the capture of Maduro as a "kidnapping".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In the United States, hundreds of people gathered in New York City's Times Square to protest against the operation, with people chanting "Hands off Venezuela" and holding up signs that stated "US Out" and "No Blood for Oil".
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Outside of New York, hundreds of people in different cities gathered to voice opposition to the strikes.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] One month after the strikes, the Venezuelan government called for a protest that gathered thousands of supporters for the release of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Oil prices did not experience a surge, which had been normal with previous conflicts in oil-producing regions; prices increased 1% as of 5 January 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The reason is believed to be that Venezuela only represents 1% of the global oil supply and high oil production by other producers, including the United States, Saudi Arabia, and Brazil.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The stock prices of companies that could become involved in Venezuela without spending money, such as oilfield service companies SLB and Halliburton, and refiners Valero Energy and Marathon Petroleum, surged on 5 January 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Some oil companies also saw increases, such as ExxonMobil and ConocoPhillips.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Bonds issued by the Venezuelan government and the state oil company PDVSA surged by 30%.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Venezuela's bonds went into default in 2017 and doubled in price during the escalating tensions in 2025.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Housing prices in Caracas rose from 20% to 50%.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In touristic sites like Margarita Island the housing prices rose up to 80%.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Some listing were paused waiting for a stabilization of the economy.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In October, before the strikes, a poll by AtlasIntel showed that approximately 64% of Venezuelans abroad support US military intervention to depose Maduro, compared with 34% within Venezuela.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] In December, a poll by Datanalisis found that 55% of Venezuelans opposed foreign military intervention while 23% supported it.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The same poll showed that Trump approval ratings rose to 42% after the attack, the highest rating since October 2025, when his approval rating was 39%.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] A poll was made by *The Economist* on 9 January, surveying 600 Venezuelan residents of different ages and sex to reflect the national population.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] Most respondents were positive about the intervention, only 13% of respondents mildly opposed the capture of Maduro.
[src:2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela/2026-united-states-intervention-in-venezuela-p03] The 18% of respondents oppose United States governance in Venezuela.
